<html>
<head>
<title>DE NAR - HOMEPAGE</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ff3300" txt="#ffffff" link="#ffffff" vlink="#ffffff">

<center><h1>"Anarchism and the Black Revolution"</h1></center>
<center><h3>Interview with Lorenzo Kom'boa Ervin</h3></center>
<center><img align=bottom src="lorenzo.gif"></center>
<p><i>Via E-mail we did the following interview. Lorenzo Komboa Ervin is an American Black Anarchist 
who served  a long time in prison, because of his activities in the Black Panther Party. 
In prison he converted himself to anarchism and after being released 
he became a well-known activist in the U.S., mainly because of his writings, 
and the book 'Anarchism and the Black Revolution'. We did this interview with 
him because we are convinced of the value of his work and because of the fact that 
he also touches a couple of topics that are painful for the anarchist movement today. 
Particulary that it is a white middle-class based group of people, unable to adress 
the needs of larger groups. If you want to find out more about Lorenzo Komboa Ervin 
check out the 
<a href="http://iww.org/~monkeywrench/">I.W.W. homepage</a>, 
but first read this interview.</i><br>
'Our apologies for the bad English from our side.'<br>

<p><b>*In our magazine we printed a lot of articles about the situation in the 
U.S. Some of our our readers ask about the importance of putting  all this 
in a Belgian anarchist magazine. But people who have been in the states tell 
us about the explosive situation among some segments of the  US 
population,especially the Black People. You've been priviliged to see both 
the European situation and the American situation. Are things really that 
'explosive' in the US?
</b>
<p>Yes, I have seen both the American and European models, and can tell you
that racism is a universal phenomenon, here I am talking about white
supremacy, not just national chauvinism or prejudice. The institutional
racism will differ from country to country, but the Blacks I visited last
October in England, those in France I correspond with, and even
non-Africans, but non-whites report a similar type of racist dynamic. The
difference is that in America, the black populaltion exists as a
semi-colony, a domestic version. When one of three young balck males are
being thrown into prison, when there is mass unemployment, conscious
disinvestment of community development funds from black communities, budge
cuts and layoffs aimed at the black community more than anyone, police
brutality where thousand are beaten and killed by racist and brutal cops, we
are then not talking about "discrimination",  we are talking about genocide.
In Europe, there is not nearly the kind of racist dictatorship as exists in
the U.S., though racism by fascist paramilitaries and cops is a problem,
especially in England where there is a substantial non-white population., 

<p><b>*Although we cannot read much about it in the media, and in the official 
history writing: the U.S. does have a socialist, and even anarchist 
tradition. I think about groups like the IWW  (partly build up 
by Immigrants) and people like Emma Goldman, Alexander Berkman, Most, etc. 
But concerning the Black community you don't hear that much about socialism 
and anarchism. One tends to think that anarchism is really  a 'White middle 
Class Thing', if  you look at the 'activists'. Lately we've been hearing 
about the Black Fist Collective, about your writings;  Black Political 
Prisoners who have outspoken anarchist opinions,... and it seems like 
something is starting to move! and in what perspective can we see those 
things? Are we talking about a couple of isolated figures and groups, or are 
things really changing? 
</b>
<p>Historically American Anarchism has been an individualist anarchism, then
later a European immigrant labor movement (1890-1930), it died out for a time,
then came back in the 1960's middle class white thing "counter-culturalism"
through the New Left, although there was a few serious political elements.

<p><b>*Concerning the new left: we have a simular tradition in europe of 
old time activists from the sixties. Most of them have become petite bourgeoisie</b>
<p>euro-bourgoisie
<p><b>, but we also still have to bear their 'traditions'. Did the sixties bring interesting
 elements to the left? If so what were the 'interesting elements' in the New Left</b>

<p>The New Left in the United States arose during the 1960's, as an extension
of the Civil rights movement, and included the Student Nonviolent
Coordinating Committee, Black Panthers, as well as the Student for a
Democratic Society, the Vietnam Anti-war movement and so on. There was a
distinct Anarchist current, which was both political and cultural. For some,
smoking dope was a badge of rebellion against authority, but so was street
fighting, and all of this was part of the same movement. In fact, in 1968
there was a worldwide student and youth rebellion, which challenged the
capitalist system like it never had since the end of the 2nd world war and
the rise of anti-colonail and radical movments in Greece, Africa [esp. Kenya
with the "Mau Mau' revolt and the Algerian civil war], Asia [Dein Bien Phu]
and other parts of the world.

<p>But the 1960's rebellion was different, though I am not sure how, from the
European Autonomist movements of the 1980's which I have read about a little
bit. Like in America, repression and reformism was used to crush both
movements. Because of that history of futility and repression, I am
beginning to think that a massive transnational commune will be necessary to
defeat capitalism and statism, and begin to establish a new way of life. If
we don't move to get ourselves organized now with a coordinated worldwide
movement, we will once again be crushed by the various governments or
statist radicals seking to seize power. I predict that ultimately what we
will see will be an international civil war when the state attacks us to
crush the new culture and if it goes into another deep tailspin. Fascism
will be a serious movement to protect capital, esp. in America, Russia, and
Eastern Europe Europe, but it will not win. I can see it as plain as day,
and we may see it before the year 2000. I try to think in terms of a broad
sweep of history, even while I am grounded in the everyday world. I don't
daydream and certainly have no crystal ball, but I can allow myself to do
something I learned in prison: to disconnect myself from daily concerns and
think deeply about an issue. 
<p><b>*Can you tell us us something about the impact of groups like the IWW, the 
Love and Rage Federation, A.R.A., Autonomous Anarchist Groups, etc.?
</b>
<p>I think that because of their failure to really grasp the race and class
dynamic, except in perhaps an idealistic way, they have not been able to
build mass movement, which reach into the working class and opressed racial
nationalities. If I spoke about each of them in turn, the IWW [of which I am
a member] has staggered for many years and literally done nothing but been a
museum or repositior of past deeds, but nothing in the contemporary phase.
It has potential, in that there is a direct action faction [for want of a
better name] which is getting stronger and stronger, but it is burdened down
with an unresponsive, defensive white bureaucracy. When I tried to create a
Black/People of Color Workers Organizing group within it to bring
African-Americans, Latinos, Asians and other non-whites, I was unmericfully
attacked. 
<p>As for both Love and Rage and the ARA, they are burdened down the disease of
"anti-fascism. It is a illness that refuses to fight the state which is
going over to fascism, and elements of the white racism in the working class
itself, they prefer to engage in vanguardism against fascist vanguard [and
marginal] elements like the Nazis or Ku Klux Klan, which has very few
members. Recently the have put the militias in their place, but still don't
see that it is the state and capitalism which makes fascism possible, and
that we are living in a police state now, it just doesn't touch the white
population--yet.
<p><b>
*When people talk about 'Black Power', they always mention once or twice 
words like black nationalism, and even segregation. What do these words mean 
to you? And secondly how do you see the Black People: are this also the 
Immigrants, Hispanics,... or only the Afro-Americans?
</b>
<p>"The Black Power movement arose in the 1960's as a progressive step away form
the reformism of D. Martin Luther King. The Student Nonviolent Coordinating
Committee which was a group I once belonged to came up with the term to
denote this new level of struggle. I want to make this clear, racial
segregation is the system of white supremacy and privelege that the civil
rights movement had come into existence to fight, the Black Power movment did
not in itself seek to oppress white persons to the degree that they were
being suppressed. But they also did not see white Liberal as allies anymore
nor the U.S. federal govenment as a protector of the rights of Blacks. Of
course tow things happened with "Black Power"  (1) it became the rallying
cry for rebellious youth; (2) it was coopted and redefined in a safe fashion
by the government and the black petit bourgeoisie and changed to signify
black capitalism and electorialism. Yes, it became a type of cultural
nationalism, which was narcissistic, xenophobic,and reformist. That type of
nationalism is still around and can be seen in Minister Louis Farrakhan of
the National of Islam. 

<p><b>* In your writings I've read  a lot lot of accusations towards white 
activists and especially those active in the antifascist struggle.  Even the 
word 'racism' is not far away. Are white activists in the US only 
occupied with some external aspects of a few outspoken fascist groups, and 
is it really that bad that they are not willing to face the basic racist 
structure of society and are guilty of racism themselves by 
not letting Black people join their movement?
</b>
<p>I will challenge any white radical who claims to be an anti-fascist and yet
does not see the components of racism in fascist ideology, and who try to
reduce the struggle as against a Left-Liberal vanguard [the good whites]
versus the Nazis [the bad whites]. This reductionism is not a serious
movement at all, but is one that obscures and evades the struggle by
retreating to the safe ground of "anti-fascism". There is mass imprisonment
of the black working class, the takeover of the political space by open
racists and fascist in both parties, racist paramilitry militias, extreme
unemployment in the black community, and every other sort of attack, and all
these people can do is talk about Nazis. The black community is herded into
ghettos where the quality of life is fragile and brutal, but these phony
anti-racists don't join in with us at all. In fact, just two weeks ago, I
attended the ARA annual convention and there were less than 25 non-white
persons, they don't try to involve the black or brown communities in their
activities. What do you call that? I call it racism and abstentionism. It is
actually a sellout to the real forces of fascism. 
 
<p><b>*Concerning the class struggle: In 'Anarchism and the Black Revolution' you 
pointed out that it isn't enough for anarchists   just to  fight the class 
war, but that they have to wipe out White Supremacy in the first place. How 
much have Black and White working class in common? Their position in society 
is both bad, but for Black people even worse. Can they form a solid 
coalition? How do you see things from this perspective? This has also a 
great importance for European working class activists, because 
of the large amount of immigrant and coloured people in the working class!
</b>
<p>What the Anarchists and retrograde Socialists do not want to consider is
that the Black working class is strategically located, have deeper
grievances vis a vis the state, and are exploited in a much more brutal
fashion than the white working class, which is an oppressor class in its own
right, even though it is exploited by capital in an elemental. The white
working class is thus a decadent class, while the black working class is a
despised class subjected to class and race oppression. The vulgar Socialist
do not want to consider that the Black Revolution is the catalyst which can
make an American revolution possible. They do not want to consider that it
is they who should follow people of color to freedom, and that it is not the
industrial white working class who will make the revolutionism. So they are
chauvanist in their own right, and this accounts for the disjointed
anti-racist and radical movements, which are afraid to raise race and class
issues.

<p><b>*Recently there is a lot to do about Cuba and the Embargo. You have been in 
Cuba and have seen the regime in action. Most anarchists don't take a stand 
pro-Cuba because of the repression against anarchists, homosexuals, 
union-members,...What's your opinion about this!</b>

<p>I have always taken the postion that I support the Cuban people vis a vis
a confrontation with U.S. imperialism, but I don't support the government,
except in the most critical fashion. Not only because of the repression of
the Cuban Anarchists and other Leftists, but because I believe that Castro
and the others subverted the course of the revolution. But we cannot do
anything but learn from this, and understand why we need a revolutionary
Anarchist movement worldwide which can intervene in such struggles. We need a
"new international", a world wide Anarchist and communal movement which
respect no border or government adminsitration. We must stand for the death
of the nation-state. We must fight for a new day, not just with force of
arms, but with community based, decentralized, mass struggles. Certainly, in
countries like Nigeria, which is a bloodthristy military regime, the tactics
would be different than in the "democratic" countries of the West, at least
at this stage. In Nigeria it is impossible to do aboveground organizing
without being arrested and shot. An Anarchist group, the Awareness League,
was arrested enmasse last year when it tried to have mass meetings of its
own members, and they just shot Ken Saro-wara and other members of the ogoni
tribe. I don't think it is an exaggeration to say that civil war is coming
and we had best be ready. We need to be able to arm and fight beside our
comrades in an international brigade just like the Communists received in
Spain in 1936 during their civil war. In fact, that is one way European
Anarchist can prove their commitment to freedom, put their asses on the line
in a country like Nigeria. I believe this would have happened in South
African if the capitalists and racist Boers had not sued for peace.

<p><b>*You pointed out he importance of groups like the Anarchist Black Cross for 
(political and social) prisoners. Most of the ABC groups are located in the 
US, although groups are active in Europe as 
well.  A former political prisoner yourself how do you see the chances for 
groups like that to grow out and to really build up a strong movement 
between the prison walls? In both Europe and the US more 
and more people end up in prison in a very scarry way. But people not always 
see the importance of support groups for political prisoners. Can you point 
out in a few words. how important this work is?   
</b>
<p>The ABC and other movements must become part of the overall mass prison
struggle, and in turn the prison struggle must become part of the
revolutionary social change movement as it develops. Otherwise we can win no
more than reforms. The American ABC's and most prison movements are
peripheral, led by white declasse intellectuals, middle class reformers or
retrograde Socialists seeking to build their movments up off the polight of
political prisoners and the destruction of the black working class. This is
a bad dynamic, blacks on the inside of the prisons, and white
radical/reformers on the outside, who do not fundamentally challenge the
system. I recently quit the National Campaign to Stop Control Unit Prisons
for that reason, and I have not been working with the North American ABC's;
I am very disappointed. An exception might be made for the Patterson, N.J.
ABC which is doing a fine job with its material and campaign "the Warchest".

<p><b>*Although a revolutionary the most part of your live you didn't start 
fighting the system as an anarchist. Is it crucial for you that a 
revolutionary  movement is also an anarchist movement? 
And more specific: can a group of people for example achieve more by not 
calling their antifascist group an anarchist antifascist group? Or is this 
just thinking in  short terms?
</b>
<p>It is crucial that a social revolutionary movement be built in America and
Europe also I might add, that is anti-authoritarian. SNCC was an
anti-authoritarian movement in its early history, and it actually created
the conditions for all of the 1960's radicalsm, including the New Left and
the Black Panther Party; [the latter through a merger in 1967-69]. Even so,
I was not an Anarchist then, but a confirmed Maoist, which was seen as being
the most dynamic momvent of that period. But in prison, after I met a black
Anarchist named Martin Sostre in 1969 while in the New York federal lockup,
after my return from Europe, and later after I started corresponded with
Anarchists [mostly European and Austrailian], I started to reassess my
political views and came to over to Anarchism. It was a hard fight with
myself, let me tell you, since most U.S. Anarchists were white middle class
types, who didn't really welcome black people.
<p><b>*Can you tell some more about M. Sostre and especially what happened to him 
after he was released?
</b>
<p>First, Martin Sostre, a Black Puerto Rican, was the first Anarchist I had
ever met or heard of. This was in 1969 when I was confined at the federal
holding center just after my being captured and returned to the U.S. from
Berlin. Sostre by this time was already an international figure, in fact the
best known political prisoner in the world, just like Mumia Abu Jamal is
today. He had been framed on drug charges by the cops in his hometown of
Buffalo, New York, and he and a female co-worker at a black and radical
bookstore he ran were railroaded to prison by an all-white jury. Although
they were "officially" charged with running drugs after an undercover cop
and an informer came into the bookstore to plant drugs, the real "crime" was
leading the rebellion against police brutality and racism which broke out in
the Summer of 1967 in Buffalo's black community.

<p>In the racist hysteria which followed the rebellion where the youth
revolted, scapaegoats were sought and found. The prosecutor primed the
all-white jury up with lurid tales of a 'communist conspiracy', 'anarchist
bomb thrower' and other prejudicial garbage, again just like the prosecutor
did in Mumia Abu Jamal's case. The truth is that Sostre had turned the
bookstore into a black cultural center to attract the community youth, and
when the rebellion broke out it was a refuge and organizing base for them.
The cops naturally didn't like it, and thus the frame-up. So Sostre went to
prison with a 10-41 years sentence,after a short farce of a trial, but
instead of being broken and forgotten, his case became the most celebrated
case of a political prisoner in the world. He also would not die and had an
unconquerable spirit. He became a jailhouse lawyer to challenge the
mistreatment of prisoners and general prison conditions. These case were
instrumental in winning many basic democratic rights for prisoners, such as
the right to red and recieve revolutionary political materials, the right
for "radical religions" like the Black muslims and the Church of the New
Song to organize and worship; also the right to hold cultural and political
gatheirngs; to perform legal work in the court cases of the prisoners; and
many other victories. He literally established the rights of prisonsers
singlehandedly, and was beaten and tortured for it.  In fact when I met him
he had filed yet another of his lawsuits and was in federal court in New
York city about it. What a dynamic and impresive individual he was. 

<p>He served ten years on this frame-up before an international mass movement of
Anarchists, Socialist, civil libertaians, labour unions, black community
activists and millions of ordinary people demanded that he be released. The
pressure was tremendous on the government and the Governor of the State of
New York pardoned him in 1977. Although active for a time when he was
released, he ran into the same kinds of problems I had about the nature of
North American Anarchism: it is do nothing, middle class and an
overwhelmingly white mileau. So he dropped out, but he would support any
radical cause dear to him over the years.

<p>I personally lost all contact with him, but would see his name pop-up now
and then. I had no inkling of his whereabouts or if he ws still alive. Then
I saw an article in the December 1993 issue of the Paterson, N.J. daily
newspaper that he was training youth to do building trades, but the white
power structure was apparently angry because he taught them to demand jobs
in the racially biased industries. In their eyes, here was the old Martin
Sostre, the dangerous hellraiser and revolutionary, just hiding his program
behind a youth works program.

<p>After I saw the article, I tried to make contact and managed to phone him
and tried to make him remember me. I am not sure that he did, but we had a
very good conversation anyway.Unfortunately I was not able to meet up with
him because my schedule was so tight, in fact I visted Canada and several
other U.S. cities in the span of weeks.
<p>We lost touch and I lost the number. I would really like to do a book on
Martin Sostre. There has only been one, by a young Socialist who lived in
Buffalo at the time of the rebellion and the trials,"The Crime of Martin
Sostre" by Vincent Copeland. It has been out of print for many years.
Someone once asked me was he still an Anarchist, I don't know, and
truthfully did not want to ask. The amazing thing is that I myself am still
an Anarchist with all the negative shit I have encoutered. He should not be
forgotten and his sacrifice should put him in the first rank of
revolutionary heroes.

<p><b>*A friend wanted me to ask you the following question: How is live for an 
ex-political prisoner? Do you still feel in your daily live repression based 
upon your conviction? For a lot of people this is far 
away from  their own situation, and hopefully most of our readers realise 
the importance of learning from the situation of both political and  
ex-political prisoners!
</b>
<p>Yes, you never forget the years of intense repression as a political
prisoner, but there is a difference in the streets. The state and its cops
will repress you as part of the daily repression of the African people in
America, but there is some mobility and a few "civil rights", but these are
being take away every day. It is hard to get oneself together after almost
15 years inside, and there are unresolved feelings of rage, depression, and
other internal ills that you have to work out for yourself. Being with a
woman, around children, and older people was hard and I had to tap a level
of love and humanity to not become bitter, callous or desparate. I worked it
all out by continuing to be active in the struggle against police brutality,
for prisoner rights, fighting racism in a serious way, and other struggles,
which gave me a purpose in life. That is how I survived prisonon in the
first place. Just fighting back in every little way, so that prison would
not overwhelm and consume me.

<p><b>*In his introduction for 'the damned of the earth' of Francis Fanon; JP 
Sartre wrote that by standing aside in the fight for freedom of the 
oppressed, one is also guilty of the crimes by the opressors. By 
standing aside he meant  not using violence to fight back. This is the never 
ending discussion between pacifism and more 'violent means of action'. You 
are not known as a pacifist, but do you see a place 
for pacifism  and pacifists in an anarchist movement?  
</b>
<p>Like Malcolm X stated you fight back by any means necessary. I do not
believe in individual terrorism or dogmatic nonviolence; they are both
extremes. I know that the state and capitalism will defend itself from any
people's movment, even reform movments, with violence and other forms of
repression. But they also use weapons of deceit such as voting, religion,
and other conformity to trick the populace into upholding the state and
believing that revolution is not necessary. Ultimately the violence in
America will come from the state, but it will take a civil war to remove the
capitalists from the scene. I see no other way, otherwise we will have more
reformism and a stronger state. That is the legacy of the 1960's movement.

<p><b>*How many copies of 'Anarchism and the Black revolution' have already been 
distributed, and do you have a sight on the impact of your work?
</b>
<p>At this point over 3,00 copies of Anarchism and the Black Revolution have
been printed and distrubuted in both pamphlet and book form since November
1993, a period of almost two years. 
<p><b>*Is the number of 300 copies sold of 'anarchism and the Black
Revolution..' correct?</b>

<p>No, over 3000 copies of Anarchism and the Black Revolution, in booklet and
book form have been sold over the last 2 years. It is a small press
bestseller. In fact, if we could get our distribution problems worked out
then we could sell many more in Canada, Europe, Africa, and other parts of
the world. Any publishers or distributors in Europe interested in publishing
a version of the book should write to me at: 145 Park Drive, Decatur, GA. 30030

<p><b>*As a last question: how will you adress the people in Europe when you come 
over for a tour of lectures? Are they things for the European movement where 
they can help out their American comrades? And vice versa?
</b>
<p>I am going to talk about anti-racist/anti-fascist politics, building an
international Anarchist resistance movment, community organizing, and the
history of the civil rights/black power movements,the latter of which is
part personal narrative. I visited England and Wales last October; I hope to
go back there on a more intense tour, to visit France and Belgium, Sweden
and Denmark. I will try to spend 6-8 weeks in Europe, which sort of depends
on if I can raise any funds to replace lost salary,and if I can get away
from all commitments. I also hope to go to Australia and maybe even South
Africa in late 1996 or early 1997. We shall see.  Thank you.
<blockquote>  
<b>Lorenzo komboa Ervin</b></blockquote>
<p><font size=-1><b>Interview: Z.B.A.</b></font>
<hr>
