<head>
<title>DE NAR - HOMEPAGE</title>
</head>
<body   link="#ff3300" vlink="#000000">
<h1> COINTELPRO and Democracy</h1><br>
<B>By Jason Wehling<br>
October 1992<br>
<br>
</B>
<br>
On April 28, 1976, following a 15-month examination of government spying  in the United States, the Senate Select Committee
on Intelligence finally  issued its findings. Aside from
numerous abuses from agencies such as the  CIA, the IRS and
Army Intelligence, the investigation uncovered massive  violations of citizens' rights by the FBI. This investigation found
the  FBI responsible for cataloging at least 26,000  individuals who would be  rounded  up in the event of a "national
emergency"; since the early 1930's, the  FBI frequently wiretapped and bugged American citizens without the benefit  of
judicial warrant; manipulating the media by disseminating
derogatory  information to the press, either anonymously or
through "friendly" news  contacts; and, the FBI was involved
in fomenting violence against various  left-wing groups.<br>
<br>
The Senate Select Committee on Intelligence's investigation
was the  culmination of many FBI exposes that were made public
throughout  the early 1970's. The Church Committee revealed in
December, 1975,  that the FBI has been used by every President
from Franklin D. Roosevelt  to Nixon for merely political
purposes. The FBI supplied secret dossiers,  conducted wiretaps and carried out physical surveillance on political 
opponents that at times included journalists, and even Congressmen  and Supreme Court Justices. <br>
<br>
But the incident that really broke the lid open on the FBI's
abuses  occurred <br>
five years earlier. On March 1971, a group calling itself the
"Citizen's  Committee to Investigate the FBI" broke into the
FBI office in Media,  Pennsylvania, and removed a large number
of classified documents.  These documents revealed that one
percent of the FBI's work was  devoted to organized crime -
mostly gambling, 30 percent were  manuals, routine forms and
similar procedural matter, and 15 percent  concerned bank
robberies, murder, rape and interstate theft. But the  majority, 54 percent, involved political groups, not criminal groups 
(40% was political surveillance, 14% concerned draft resistance). Of  that 54 percent, less than one percent related to
"right-wing" groups,  while left-wing groups made up 95 percent of the documents.<br>
<br>
These documents exposed a type of political disruption program
the FBI  referred to as "COINTELPRO". COINTELPRO or COunter
INTELligence  PROgrams were designed not for criminal activity, but - in the FBI's  own words - to "disrupt and destabilize", "cripple", "destroy", or  otherwise "neutralize" dissident political groups in the United States.   <br>
<br>
The level of FBI surveillance was incredible. The FBI headquarters alone  had developed over 500,000 domestic intelligence files. Nearly 250,000  first class letters were opened
and photographed in the U.S. by  intelligence agencies between
1953 and 1973, producing a computerized  index of nearly 1.5
million names. The FBI admits than in the period  between <br>
1956 and mid-1971 it conducted 2218 separate COINTELPRO actions,  2305 warrantless phone taps, 697 illegal bugs, and
intercepted and  opened 57,846 pieces of mail. These figures
merely reflect admitted  abuses.<br>
<br>
Political manipulation by the FBI was not random, but as the
stolen  documents showed, it was aimed specifically at left-of-center and liberal  groups - groups like the New Left, the
Communist Party U.S.A. (CPUSA)  and the Socialist Workers
Party (SWP). The SWP's case is particularly  interesting
because they sued and in March 1988, eventually won a 
$264,000 suit against the FBI for violating their constitutional right to  privacy. <br>
<br>
Declassified documents made available through the Freedom of 
Information Act (FOIA) show that on October 12, 1961, the FBI
began  the "Socialist Workers Party (SWP) Disruption Program".
These documents  now show that the FBI, for over a decade
worked to neutralize the SWP as  a political force. FBI activities included attempting to destroy the 1961  campaign of a
black socialist for Manhattan borough President,  tried to 
discredit Clifton DeBarry - the SWP's 1964 Presidential candidate, tried  to divide socialists from supporters of an independent black candidate  in San Francisco, and incited an
attack on socialist Fred Halstead during  his candidacy for
President in 1968. The SWP had broken no laws - the  motivation for this program was completely political in nature.<br>
<br>
When questioned about its fetish for destroying mostly left-wing groups,  the FBI replied that leftists groups by their
very nature are more prone  to violence. Therefore, the FBI
thought, it was necessary to stop the left  at whatever cost.
This excuse for partisan warfare is completely  hypocritical <br>
and ironic, for the FBI itself often committed and encouraged
violence,  and in particular against left-wing and liberal
groups. Examples of this  include the Secret Army Organization
(SAO) of San Diego. The SAO was  a crypto-fascist outfit that
was created and financed by the FBI. The SAO  activities
ranged from burglary and mail theft, to bombings,  kidnapping,
assassination plots and attempted murder.<br>
<br>
Although the FBI has infiltrated right-wing groups such as the
Ku Klux  Klan, the overwhelming majority of COINTELPRO has
been directed  towards the left. In fact, the FBI has actually
assisted many right-wing  extremists such as the Minutemen and
the John Birch Society. <br>
<br>
After the disclosures of using illegal methods and exposes of
massive  abuses of power, the FBI publicly stated that all
COINTELPRO operations  had been terminated and would refrain
from using such programs in the  future. This was only half-true and very misleading. The government did  abandon theacronym COINTELPRO - the word itself no longer appears in  FBI
documents - but COINTELPRO-type operations have never stopped, 
continuing even today. According the Ward Churchill, the
author of  The COINTELPRO Papers, "during the 3 years
(1972-1974) following the  point at which COINTELPRO was
supposedly terminated, the frequency  with which the Bureau
engaged in warrentless bugging and wiretapping  increased
dramatically."<br>
<br>
The latest examples of the casualties from COINTELPRO include
the  Committee In Solidarity with the People of El Salvador
(CISPES) and  Earth First!. From 1981 to 1984, Frank Varelli
was paid by the FBI to  infiltrate  CISPES, which was a non-violent group working to change  U.S. policies toward El
Salvador. According to Varelli, the FBI was  attempting to
"break" CISPES by using break-ins, bogus publications,  disrupting public events, planting guns on CISPES members, and
even  seducing CISPES leaders in order to get blackmail photos.<br>
<br>
Similarly, the environmental group Earth First! was infiltrated by FBI  agent Michael Tait, who encouraged sabotage. Eventually on May 31, 1989, Tait  was used as a witness to prosecute Dave Forman, Mark Baker, Mark Davis,  and Peg Millett for
attempting to cut down power lines in Arizona. But  even more
blatant is the possibility of FBI involvement in the car 
bombing of Earth First! organizers Darryl Cherney and Judi
Bary on May 24, 1990.  Originally, the FBI attempted to charge
Cherney and Bary with their own  bombing. The FBI even pulled
finishing nails from Bary's window trim  during FBI raids on
her house in an attempt to link the nails with those  found in
the car bomb.<br>
<br>
The FBI's campaign against political freedom goes much deeper
than  mere "disruption" of political groups, but has been
involved in plans to  actually neutralize the democratic
process itself. According to a former  FBI informant, Louis E.
Tackwood, the FBI was involved in a plan  which  entailed
planting a number of agent-provocateurs both inside and outside  the 1972 Republican Convention in San Diego. Agents were
to infiltrate  groups planning to demonstrate against the
Vietnam war. These agents  were then to provoke street battles
with police outside the Convention,  while agents inside were
to have planted explosives, timed to e xplode simultaneously
with the riot outside. This action would have set  up the
popular support necessary for President Nixon to declare a 
"national emergency" and arresting all "radicals", "militants"
and  "left-wing revolutionaries".<br>
<br>
This may sound fantastic, but in the spring of 1970, William
Howard, a  Washington D.C. reporter for Newhouse Publications,
ran a story about  a "contingency plan to cancel the 1972
elections." According to Howard,  Nixon ordered the Rand
Corporation think tank to do a "feasibility study"  of the
cancellation possibility in 1972, under the auspices  of
Nixon's  concern about possible "disruption by the left." 1972
may seem too far  off to worry about, but this type of plan
was resurrected in 1984 under  the Reagan administration.During the Iran-Contra hearings, a contingency  plan to suspend the Constitution was exposed. This plan was to be put 
into effect in a planned U.S. invasion of Nicaragua if it
sparked  wide-spread protests.<br>
<br>
Remember during this election year, when one becomes very
frustrated that  the only choice is between the two wings of
the Business party, that the  FBI has played a paramount role
in subverting any alternative third  party, especially those
on the left. With the emergence of people like  Pat Buchanan,
David Duke and George Bush and things like Ballot Measure 9 
here in Oregon, it is obvious that the political pendulum has
swung too  far to the right. It is organizations like the FBI,
who use tax-payer  money to make sure that politics keep to
the right. In times like these  when people are crying for
change, it is important to keep in mind why  and how things
have gotten this way.  <br>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.knooppunt.be/~de_nar"><img align=left src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~de_nar/smallnar.gif"></a>
<br>
<br>
De Nar, Pb 104, 1210 Brussel 21<br>
