<title>DE NAR - HOMEPAGE</title>
</head>
</body>
<p>  <h1>SPATIAL DECONCENTRATION AND THE SQUATTERS MOVEMENT</h1>
<p><h3>BY ALGERT SHORTZ</h3>
<p> During the 1960's the Untied States was going through some of the most
turbulent times since the Civil War. Freedom rides in the south and freedom
riots in the north were rocking the nation. Poor people and people of color
were fed up with the ruling elite's stranglehold on the American people. No
longer were people of color willing to take " the back seat of the bus" and
segregation's limit to "freedom and equality for all" was challenged. People
were willing to violently oppose the government's unconstitutionality.
<p> The social upheaval of the 60's caused great concern for the ruling elite.
By the 1970's these concerns turned into studies and eventually led to plans
to "spatially deconcentrate" the urban areas where poor people and people of
color were organizing to resist the state. These highly secret military plans
set out to break up inner city neighborhoods and relocate people to the outer
suburbs where they would be far enough apart to keep from organizing. Those
not willing to go would be forced out by high rents and condemned buildings
and be herded into shelters.
<p> Part of the plan was to allow the buildings to deteriorate so that they
would be unsafe to live in. The residents would be forced to relocate. Then
the fire department would usually go in and cut out some of the main joists
in the buildings and cut a huge whole in the roof to expose the inside to the
elements. This would ensure that the buildings would be too costly to repair
and keep out would be squatters. Then the city would board up the buildings
and leave them to rot for years. Many were demolished leaving a pile of
rubble and making neighborhoods look like bombed out war zones. 
 Boarding up buildings and tearing down buildings effectively created a
housing shortage and every capitalist knows that a shortage of something
highly demanded causes the price of that something to rise. This increase in
rent made it difficult for those who were losing their homes due to this
process to find a new home they could afford. Out of this, the homeless
population in New York City grew from 20,000 in 1980 to 100,000 in 1990.
Contrast that with 250,000 vacant apartments in the city and the picture
starts to become clear. The city was warehousing apartments to create a class
of homelessness.
<p> Professional shelter bureaucrats and liberal homeless advocates saw the
homeless epidemic as an opportunity to create a new shelter industry. They
could confuse the homeless into accepting an alternative to housing by
offering a transitional bed in military style barracks. By keeping the poor
moving, dispersed and disenfranchised within the penal-like shelter system,
the state hopes to maintain the people in a situation of powerless and
deathly conditions. This became the dominant strategy to control and limit
the resistance of the oppressed.
<p> Those who saw the obvious solution to the homeless problem began to take
direct action, they began to squat. After all, with all of the thousands of
abandoned and warehoused apartments and empty land, it seemed crazy to
suggest that thousands of homeless victims of the governmental assault live
in barracks. This was poison to the state's military plan.
<p> Some of the squatting ideology came from the Diggers movement. The Diggers,
a small band of 17th century visionaries led by Gerrard Winstanely,
proclaimed all private property to be the result of murder and theft. After
the end of the monarchy, they announced plans to develop all wastelands and
common lands into productive, communal farms and spread the idea of free,
mass-cultivation of the earth. With half a dozen or so companions, they began
to dig the common land on St. Georges Hill, a location outside London. 
 As the Diggers began this process, they expected others to join them, give
up their lands and estates, and submit it to the needs of the larger
community. They disclaimed any intention of meddling with any man's property
but said they planned only to cultivate the waste and the common land. The
Diggers were mostly poor men who were victims of the economic recession. They
did not demand any political rights but they did demand the elementary right
to survival. 
<p> The Diggers never numbered more than a hundred. Their efforts were
repeatedly and sometimes cruelly quashed by indignant neighbors bent on
protecting their own rights. They were also beaten by paid hooligans and
fined by magistrates; their cattle were driven away, their seeding torn up,
and their flimsy huts burned down. After a year the colony scattered forever,
but it had, consciously or not, effected some of the ideas most important to
19th & 20th century political and economics radicalism.
<p> These ideas are inherent to the squatting movement today. Squatters believe
that housing is the fundamental foundation to any society. The lack of
affordable and decent housing imposes tremendous hardship on the social/human
condition. Homelessness, the infestation of drugs, the segregation of the
neighborhood, gentrification and class war result from the profit motive
system called Real Estate.
<p> The states reaction to the squatters movement has been one of great concern.
They say that if squatting succeeds that there will be a "great land rush".
Their biggest fear is not a land rush but that once people begin to take back
the land they will become empowered. Because squatting requires people to
organize and work together for the common good, the powers that be fear that
people will realize that they alone have the power to resolve the problems
facing society today without the intervention of the state. In essence,
squatting threatens the very nature of a system that forces its' subjects
into a state hopelessness then offers its' assistance only to make sure that
the subjects feel servitude to that system. The idea being that you never
bite the hand that feeds you. 
<p> Since 1986 roughly 500 people from diverse racial, ethnic, cultural and
political backgrounds have chosen to squat on the lower east side of New York
City, defying greedy politicians, official leftists and police attacks. The
squatters here have taken a total of about 10-15 buildings with approximately
250-300 apartments. They have taken buildings that were once burned out
shells and invested enormous amounts of time and money into renovations. Just
surviving during the time when a building is first opened is extremely tough.
No electricity, no plumbing, missing floors and walls, and gaping holes in
the roof make life unbearable, even impossible, especially during the winter.
Eventually, as time goes by, repairs are made and the building begins to feel
more like home. One can't help but feel pride in taking on the task of
forging one's own destiny and planting the seeds of growth. But there is a
price!
<p> Those seeds of growth are constantly threatened by the poisonous tentacles
of the establishment. The states militaristic plan to systematically herd the
masses into the slaughterhouse shelter system where diseases like AIDS and TB
run rampant has stood firm. The city is always on the offensive with massive
police attacks and evictions. If that doesn't work the buildings mysteriously
go up in flames. This means that squatters must always be on the defensive.
Weekly eviction watch meetings and plans to come to the aid of a squat under
attack are necessary. Some squats even keep a stock of bricks, bottles and
moltovs on their roofs for the time when their homes may be threatened. 
<p> When a building is under attack, the city sends in thousands of cops in full
riot gear, strategically placing snipers on surrounding rooftops and using
urban police tanks to drag away overturned cars that squatters use to
barricade off the street. Then the cops proceed to cut through the steel
barricades that squatters use to weld themselves in. When the cops do get
inside the tenants are usually beaten to the ground and arrested. Fortunately
most of the charges never stem past misdemeanor trespassing and resisting
arrest. After they have removed everyone from the building they seal them up
with steel gates and place a couple of cops on 24 hour duty. Its' very hard
to get a building back after an eviction. 
<p> The struggle continues even in the face of losing several buildings to fire
and many to eviction. Just in the past month of this writing the city
illegally moved in to evict three buildings on 13th street. A neighborhood
group who calls itself the Lower East Side Coalition Housing Development
(LESCHD) and is controlled by councilman Antonio Pagan, has been trying to
take the buildings claiming they are vacant and are a "blighting influence"
on the neighborhood. Pagan who is a well known pro-landlord profiteer and
(LESCHD) say they want to convert the buildings into "low income" housing
that would revert to market rate housing in fifteen years. This is a ploy
that is always used by the city and groups like this. They say that they need
the buildings to build low income housing or housing for the elderly and that
the squatters are in the way. The reason is to convince the rest of the
community that that the squatters are blocking their efforts to help the
poor. The scam usually works. Squatters argue that there are hundreds of
other buildings that are abandoned, vacant and unused to choose from, why
take our building. The truth is they just want the squatters out.
 <p>The squatters, who formed the East 13th street Homesteaders Coalition,
obtained a Temporary Restraining Order (TRO) through State Supreme Court
Judge Elliott Wilk. The (TRO) prevents the city from taking any action toward
evicting the buildings without "due process." Judge Wilk questioned the
city's allowing abandonment for so many years, and he asked why the city has
been holding housing stock.
<p> Since that time two of the five buildings and the first floor of a third
building have been evicted. The city's attorneys went to the state appeals
courts to have the TRO overturned, failed, and then filed "vacate orders"
against the homesteaders claiming the buildings were in "imminent danger" of
collapse. Judge Wilk then interrupted the initial TRO hearing and held a
"hearing within the hearing" on the physical stability of the buildings.
After several days of listening to witnesses the Judge ruled against the
city. The city then launched a further appeal against this. The appeals court
set a September date for a full hearing on the city's motion.
<p> But, due to peculiarities in New York State law, such a decision "stays" or
nullifies Judge Wilk's "no evictions" order pending the September hearing.
This means the city may evict the homesteaders from their homes, even though
the only factual and legal findings by a court are that such evictions are
illegal.
<p> This just goes to show what lengths the state will go to stomp out
resistance. The war against the poor rages in this country and congress has
been stepping up the battle with blows to the constitution. Just recently
they voted on an anti-terrorism bill that would give the president
dictatorial powers while eliminating the 1st, 4th, 6th, and 7th amendment to
the constitution. The recent developments in this country have frightened a
society of people who have already been terrorized by policies that drove a
wedge between the middle and upper classes making millions of working class
people either homeless or working for slave wages. 
<p> The ruling elite are using the media as a tool to deceive the people into
thinking that our constitution allows to much freedom and that by eliminating
these freedoms, the state can better protect it's citizenry. This deceit is
the work of a long drawn out plan to terrorize a nation into giving up it's
inaliable rights and freedoms and create a one world government where
servitude to a corporate dictatorship reign supreme. We must remember that
not long ago millions were led away to the gas chambers by a fascist dictator
run amuck. The laws that were passed by Hitler's Germany were frighteningly
similar to the laws being debated in congress now. Laws that allow the
government to illegally spy on and infiltrate any group it considers a threat
to its' master plan by labeling it a terrorist group. As more people expose
this information the swifter the thought police must convince people that
pedaphiles are lurking the internet to verbally molest their children so that
people will beg them to come in and police the information superhighway. They
fear this information superhighway is bringing people together from all over
the world at a grass roots level and must be monitored and censored.
<p> This crackdown on our freedom has been obvious to squatters and local
activists. We have become victims of a genocidal, profit driven motive to
force out entire communities of poor working class people and replace them
with people who can afford $1500-$2000 dollar a month rents. By doing so
millions have already become homeless and the states only solution to this
has been to house them in military style barracks that are more like
concentration camps for the homeless. We realize that the system that created
this problem in the first place has no real intentions of trying to fix it.
We know that in order to get help we are going to have to take matters into
our own hands and take back the abandoned and warehoused land and cultivate
it for ourselves. By doing so we have the opportunity to find ways to work
together to plant the roots for a society that is truly for the people, by
the people.   

</body>
</html>        
       


