<title>DE NAR - HOMEPAGE</title>
</head>
<body link="ff3300" vlink="000000">


  <h1>The Situation Of Political Prisoners In   Western Europe:  
 An
  Overview</h1>
  
  <p>The "European Order" seems to also show its effects in the 
  conditions and treatment of political prisoners. With a few
  exceptions, it is fair to say that most   political prisoners  
 in
  Western
  Europe face more or less the same detention   conditions. But  
 of
  course
   these    conditions    affect   individual  prisoners   in a  
 different
  subjective
  manner,  for  example  Georges  Cipriani   in   France (where  
 the
  conditions
   are   especially   rigid) has   been  struggling   for years  
 against
  forced
  psychiatric care despite his poor health.
  <p>This overview, unfortunately, does not deal with the several
 
  prisoners from colonial or semi-colonial states (in France, for
  example) or the hundreds of  Kurdish  prisoners   in Germany.  
 For
  the
  latter (due to permanent repression because of the ban on
  organizations), even the  lawyers themselves  barely   have a  
 full
  grip on
  the  situation,  and  with  the   former,  we   aren't really  
 sure
  ourselves
  about the real extent of the   levels  of   imprisonment. But  
 even
  with
  things  that  are  "closer  to   home"   -   namely prisoners  
 from
  (former)
  armed  organizations -  we cannot  claim that   this overview  
 is
  entirely
  comprehensive, not the least because of the very difficult
  communications situation.
  <p>The notion of  political prisoners   is  only   applied in  
 this
  text to
  those prisoners who, in their praxis, have exhibited a clear
  orientation of struggle against  capitalism  and   the state,  
 not
  those
  who  have  collaborated   with   state     institutions   or   
 their
  representatives
   and/or  took  the  route  of  renunciation  or  a   "political
 solution".
  <p><b>Spain</b>
  <p>In  Spanish  prisons,  there  are  56    prisoners   from   
 the
  reconstituted
   (illegal)  Communist Party  of Spain,  the PCE(r),  and from  
 GRAPO.
  After
  long - and very successful - years of struggle, they achieved
   regroupment,  thus  resulting  in  two prisoners'  collectives
 inside
  the
  prisons: In Herrera de la Mancha there's the women's collective
   "Carmen    Lopez",  and    in Sorias   there  is   the men's  
 collective
  "Carlos
   Marx".    Both  collectives    are  engaged    in  intensive  
 educational
  work and
  study significant theoretical and political texts. Through the
  production of postcards,  souvenirs, key  chains, and  so on,  
 they
  have
  been able to finance themselves. In  1989/90   they struggled  
 for
  14
  months by means of a hungerstrike to protest the breakup of the
   collectives,  but  unfortunately  they were  not successful.  
 During
  this
  hungerstrike,  comrade Jose  Manuel  Sevillano   died. Today,  
 the
  prisoners
  are isolated from one another, are subjected to very severe
  conditions, and many of them are very sick.
  <p>The exact number of Basque prisoners  from ETA  is unknown  
 (to
  us), but
  the number is approximately 600 (with 60 of these in France).
  
  <p><b>Italy</b>
  
   <p>There  are  16  women  and  59  men spread  out between  14
 different
  
  prisons.  (In  the 1960s   and 70s,   there  were   more than  
 3,000
  political
  prisoners in Italy.)
  <p>All comrades still in prison today are members of fighting 
  communist guerrilla  organizations,  groups,   or split-offs,  
 for
  example
  the  BR/PCC  (Red  Brigades/Fighting     Communist   Party).   
 Some
  comrades have
  been in prison for a long time, while others were just recently
  arrested (1993).
       <p>Prisoners    from    the  former   'Partito Guerilla'  
 (Guerrilla
  Party), an
  split-off  from  the  BR  (Red  Brigades),    have   founded   
 the
  prisoners'
  collective 'Wotta Sitta' and have for  years been  contributing
 to
   developments    within  the    international  revolutionary   
 movement.
  There
   are even   still  two   comrades in   prison  from   the NAP  
 ('Nuclei
  Armati
  Proletari',  Armed Proletarian  Nuclei), a  group   in Naples  
 which
  existed
  prior to the Red Brigades.
     <p>In  addition  to  Italian  prisoners,   there  are   also
 Palestinian
  
  prisoners from a variety of organizations being held in Italian
   prisons.  They  are  subject to  different   conditions, for  
 example
  they
  are not allowed to read or write in their mother  language (a  
 de
  facto
  ban,  therefore, on  visits, writing,  and   reading). What's  
 more,
  these
  prisoners   are   continually   under   pressure   from   the  
 Zionist
  security
  services,  to whom  the Italian  authorities often  turn over  
 files
  and
  information.
  
  <p><p>Germany<p>
  <p>During the past few years,  various prisoners  from the  RAF
 and
  the
   resistance  have  been  released  from   prison,  some   after
 completing
  their
  sentences,  others with  probation for  their remaining  years.
 Even
  Germany's longest-held political prisoner, Irmgard Moeller, was
  released  after  22 years,   and  Christine   Kuby (seriously  
 ill)
  after 18
  years.  Apart from  those prisoners  not (yet)  sentenced and  
 those
  who
  are collaborating, there are still 9 revolutionary prisoners in
  Germany.
  <p>Hanna Krabbe, who has been  in prison  for  20   years, is  
 now
  alone in
  Lubeck  prison  following  the   release   of   Moeller   and  
 Kuby.
  Sieglinde
   Hoffman,  who  was  due to  be released  after completing  her
 15-year
  sentence, was betrayed by a traitor arrested in the former East
  Germany and  sentenced   to life   in  prison.   Rolf Clemens  
 Wagner
  (arrested
  in Zurich, sentenced to two life terms, and, again because of
  statements from a traitor, now confronted with  a   new trial  
 and
  the
  prospect of  another "life"  sentence) and  Rolf Heissler  have
 been
  in
  prison for 15 years. Helmut Pohl,  whose health  is very  poor,
 has
  been
  in prison since 1989,  after having  already served   7 years  
 in
  prison in
   the  1970s.  Adelheid    Schulz,  Brigitte    Mohnhaupt, and  
 Christian
  Klar
  (who  recently  was   on   hungerstrike   to   protest   his   
 prison
  conditions)
  was been isolated  in   tough condition   for  more   than 12  
 years.
  Heidi
  Schulz has being denied necessary medical treatments, had them
  delayed, or only been treated to such  a degree  as to  prevent
 the
  most
  serious effects. Eva Haule has been in prison  for   9 years,  
 and
  she,
   too,  is  facing  a  new trial  because of  statements from  a
 traitor.
  
  <p><b>France</b>
  
  <p>Two men and  two women  prisoners  from   'Action Directe'  
 (an
  armed group
   which  was   active until   the  mid-1980s)   have struggled  
 against
  isolation
  detention and their destruction  and for  their identity  since
 the
  mid-1980s,  usually   by   means   of   hungerstrikes.   The   
 health
  situation of
  Georges Cipriani is especially  serious. Four   other accused  
 AD
  members
   were sentenced  to 30  years in  prison in  July 1995  for a  
 serious
  of
  actions and attacks between 1982 and 1986.
  
  <p><b>Belgium</b>
  
  <p> There are  four political  prisoners, one  woman and  three
 men,
  in
  Belgium, all from the CCC ('Cellules Communistes Combattentes',
   Fighting  Communist  Cells),  a  fighting  initiative  which  
 launched
  armed
  struggle in Belgium in 1984.
   <p>All four  were arrested  on December  16,  1986,   and in  
 the
  following
  months the CCC were defeated and their legal structures were
  undermined  by  state agents.  The prisoners   were subjected  
 to
  total
  isolation until they went on trial, when all four comrades were
  sentenced  to  life  in  prison.   They  have   taken   part   
 in
  revolutionary
   debates   over   the   past   few   years   by   means   of   
 collective
  statements.
  <p>Under  Belgian  law,  prisoners  serving  life   in prison  
 are
  eligible for
   release  after  10  years. But  since the  CCC prisoners  will
 neither
  "admit guilt" nor  express "remorse"   for  their   deeds, it  
 will
  take
   international  solidarity  and  massive  pressure  to win  the
 freedom
  of
  these four comrades.
  
  <p><b>Denmark</b>
  
  <p>We know of five "internationalist" political prisoners in 
  Denmark, four Danes  and one  Swiss  citizen,   all sentenced  
 for
  robbing a
   post   office   in   Copenhagen.   Marc   Rudin,   the Swiss  
 prisoner
  (sentenced
  to  9 years  in prison),  was arrested  at   the Turkey-Syria  
 border
  in 1992
  on  an  international  warrant  and was   eventually deported  
 to
  Denmark
  after spending a  year and   a half   in  prison   in Turkey.  
 (Marc
  Rudin was
  active   for a   decade  as   a comrade   in  the   PFLP. The  
 millions
  stolen in
   Copenhagen    went    to    benefit   the  struggle   of the  
 Palestinian
  people.)
   Marc Rudin has become especially well known because of his 
  political art work. Rudin did art for the PFLP  under the  name
 of
  Jihad
  Mansour.
