<DOCOLDNO>IA024-000248-B022-356</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.knooppunt.be:80/~daniel/krause.html 194.10.201.200 19970108100755 text/html 7426
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: CERN/3.0
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 11:07:15 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 7219
Last-Modified: Thursday, 02-Jan-97 00:13:54 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Audrie Krause</TITLE>
<P></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#7FAE9E" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="http://www.corpwatch.org/trac/images/krause-head.GIF" 
WIDTH=564 HEIGHT=144> </CENTER>

<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10
CELLPADDING=10 WIDTH="95%">

<tr valign=top>
<td valign=top>


<P>

<IMG SRC="http://www.corpwatch.org/trac/images/audrie.gif" WIDTH=123 
HEIGHT=146 ALIGN=RIGHT>
It started in the early 1970s as ARPANET, a taxpayer-financed project of the military-industrial complex. For a long time, its only users were military officials and members of the nation's academic and scientific elite.

<P>
Over time, demand for commercial access to the Internet grew. Researchers and graduate students who had left academia encouraged their private-sector employers to lobby for commercial access to E-mail in order to foster collaborative work with colleagues 






around the world. 

<H2> <B>"Large corporate mergers might ultimately reduce consumer
choice and content."</B> </H2> <P> By the late 1980s, the
Internet was fully opened to commercial interests, unleashing a
dramatic increase in Internet use. According to the <A
HREF="http://www.mids.org/ids3">Matrix Information
and Directory Services</A> (MIDS), which tracks In

ternet demographics, the Internet has been growing about 100% a year since 1988, essentially doubling in size each year. <A HREF="http://www.mids.org/prdomreg.html">Statistics</A> on trends in Internet domains indicate that there are approximately ten tim






es as many commercial domains as organizational domains.

<P>

<IMG SRC="http://www.corpwatch.org/trac/images/bad-guy-4.gif" WIDTH=134 
HEIGHT=190 ALIGN=LEFT>
There are many reasons for the Internet's rapid growth. Vice President Al Gore's popularization of the "information superhighway" put information technology policy on the national political agenda. The introduction of graphical interface software made the






 technology much more user-friendly. And the cost of a home computer became more affordable for more consumers.

<P>
So far, the growing commercialization of the Internet hasn't interfered with public interest use of the technology. But Gordon Cook, editor and publisher of the <A HREF="http://pobox.com/cook/"><I>Cook Report on the Internet, </I></A>warns that things cou






ld change in the next couple of years.

<P>
Industry demand for greater bandwidth, combined with the move to "measured-use" pricing which has already been initiated by MCI, could ultimately lead to higher consumer costs for Internet access. Cook says the Big Four national "backbone" providers -- MC






I, Sprint, UUNet Technologies and BBN Planet, are the corporations to watch because they could easily initiate a price war that would drive hundreds of smaller Internet service providers out of business. Both cost and content could be affected. 

<P>
What's more, as an article which recently appeared in <A HREF="http://www.thenation.com/issue/960603/0603mill.htm"><I>The Nation</I></A><I> </I>warns, progressives will need to pay attention if the democratic promise of the Internet is to be realized. In 






a reference to media giants like NBC, ABC, CBS, CNN, Sony, Tele-Communications, Inc., and Viacom, the author, Mark Crispin Miller cautions that: 

<P>
"The same gigantic players that control the elder media are planning shortly to absorb the Internet, which could be transformed from a thriving common wilderness into an immeasurable de facto cyberpark for corporate interests . . ." 

<P>
Internet congestion, pricing, access, and governance are all issues of concern. Among the questions that need to be addressed are: Who owns the pipes? What kinds of regulations will protect the consumer and public interests? And, will corporate hogging of






 bandwidth lead to increasing congestion, "brownout" problems and a usage-based pricing regime?

<P>
Political control of Internet content is another key issue. While government censorship is a major concern for Net activists (and the most significant threat to the substance of the Internet today), large corporate media and technology industry mergers mi






ght ultimately reduce consumer choice and reduce content, while advertising may increase dramatically. However, these are not perceived as a problem by those who oppose all forms of regulation. This cyberlibertarian vision is not only simplistic, it's dan






gerous.

<H2>
<B>"What kinds of regulations will protect the consumer and public interests?"</B>
</H2>
<P>
Missing from the picture is an understanding of the potentially helpful role that government regulation can play. For example, by enforcing and strengthening anti-trust laws the government can promote fair competition. Netscape is beginning to understand 






this; the company has raised anti-trust issues in its effort to fend off Microsoft's attempt to capture the Internet browser market. Making Internet access affordable to our nation's schools and libraries is also an appropriate role for federal regulators






. And although we may not be there yet, at some point Internet access will be so pervasive that the definition of universal service will have to be modified to include it. 

<P>

<IMG SRC="http://corpwatch.org/trac/images/computer-web-rev.gif" WIDTH=173 
HEIGHT=172 ALIGN=RIGHT>
While these are appropriate issues for regulators to address, I confess to a certain amount of ambivalence about government regulatory processes, since they can easily be derailed or corrupted by well-financed interests. It seems to me that the best way t






o ensure fairness is to encourage full participation in the discussion. To that end, I'm concerned less about whether government regulators or private corporations control the Internet than I am about making sure the public's interest is represented in th






e decision-making process. We need to monitor our state regulatory commissions, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) and Congress. We also need to put pressure on these institutions to allow for more democracy in the decision-making process.

<P>
And we need to be on guard if we hope to avoid the sort of future described below by terminally-hip <A HREF="http://www.hotwired.com/wired/3.01features/shitlist.html"><I>HotWired</I></A><I>:</I> 

<P>
"Redmond, Wash., Noon; Jan. 20, 2001 (via Microsoft Network) -- During swearing-in ceremonies held today on the steps of Whitehouse 97 (formerly Building #9), Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates shocked the business world by announcing a hostile takeover of eve






ry company listed on the New York and Nasdaq stock exchange minutes before taking the oath of office as 44th president of the United States."

<P><br><br>
<B>Audrie Krause </B>(<a href="mailto:"akrause@igc.org">akrause@igc.org</A>) is the founder of <A HREF="http://www.netaction.org">NetAction</A>, a new non-profit working to educate the public and promote grassroots citizen action on technology-based socia






l and political issues. She previously served as Executive Director of Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility.
<P><br><br>

</td></tr></table>
<p>
<hr noshade size="0.5" width="800">

</body>
</html>
