<HTML>

<HEAD><TITLE>MBADIIS</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY><Body bgcolor="#191970" text="#ffffff" Link="#00ff00" vLink="#ffa500" aLink="#ff0000"><CENTER><IMG  VSPACE=0 HSPACE=20 SRC="mb1d.gif"><P><font size=8><B>ADIIS<BR>
<Font size=6> Lisboa, Portugal</center></B><BR><BR>
<Font Size=3>
<H1>AIMS:</H1>

The project by ADIIS has the following objectives:<BR><BR>
<OL><LI>Development of innovative implementation strategies of both placement and orientation, in the social integration of poor and unqualified young people, so as to get them out of unemployment, preferable through self-employment or the creation of small enterprises.
</LI><LI>Development of training programs and of educational material in the insertion of urban young people through economic and cultural activities, resorting to the use of media related technologies.
</LI><LI>Training of vocational trainers and other technical staff towards supporting the insertion process.</LI><LI>Support towards the development of local development initiatives on both community and cultural grounds.</LI>
</OL><BR><BR>

<H1>ACTIVITIES:</H1>
<OL><LI>Educational training of vocational trainers.</LI>
<LI>Self-employment training action.</LI><LI>Development of both placement and orientation systems in the process of social and professional integration, through interchanges by local development agencies.</LI>
Development of training programmes towards self-employment in the
media area, as well as its necessary educational material.</LI>
<LI>The creation of a manual for both vocational trainers and other technical staff, in the area of social - economic integration of young urban people at risk (texts, audio and visual material and CD-ROM).</LI><LI>The organisation of an international seminar under the theme of "Social integration in urban areas through both economic and cultural activities".</LI></OL><BR><BR>

<H1>DATES:</H1>
<UL><LI>Setting and Preparation: September 1995 - December 1995</LI>
<LI>Training of vocational trainers: November 1996 - April 1997</LI><LI>Training towards self-employment in media: October 1996 - June 1998</LI><LI>Development of both placement and orientation systems: October 1997 - October 1998</LI><LI>Development of educational programmes and materials: January 1996 - December 1997 </LI><LI>Manual production and creation: November 1996 - November 1997</LI><LI>International seminar: November 1997</LI><LI>Final national evaluation: October 1998</LI></UL><BR><BR>


<H1>TARGET GROUPS:</H1>

At the national level, this project is directed towards young people below the age of 20, living in the Lisbon area - inculding its suburbs, and from low income family aggregates, who have abandoned school less than 1 year prior to the project's starting date, have never found stable employment conditions, that find themselves at risk of social rupture but have, nevertheless, developed some form of activity or contact - even if sporadic, interest or capabilities for cultural and communication related activities. The amount of young people to be selected as beneficiaries of this training action will be 16. As regards support towards self-employment and/or the creation of small enterprises, this project is open to the orientation of young people wich may amount to a minimum of 50 - including the 16 already benefiting from this self-employment training scheme - who wish to develop - by themselves or with associates - a project of self-employment or create a small business in the area of social and cultural community support.<BR>
Beyond these final young beneficaires; the aim is to include, at the beginning of the project in question, the posterior development of training in the technical - professional area of their competence.<BR><BR>


<H1>ACTION AMBIT:</H1>

At the national level, the emergency of this project came about through the
realization that, in big urban areas such as Lisbon and its suburbs, young people from low income families leave school so as get close to particular activity sectors such as cultural and communication industries, groups (including rock groups, the big opening up the record industry, the videogames, and so on), led by the fascination created on them by the enormous media divulgence of such activities, and stimulated by ways of living that are close to them. The closeness to these active sectors can not usually be translated by a framing or effective connection to those sectors alone, leading those young people into an accumulation of personal and social conflicts and leaving them at risk of ruptures with the educational system, their family core or even at the mercy of delinquency. The absence of technical and professional competencies is <I>per si</I>, one of the reasons for their non-integration in the active environment, give the reduced predominance of these particular areas in the educational system and coupled with the absence of any guidance towards their social-economic integration.<BR><BR>

<H1>Local Contact</H1>

José Henriques<BR>

E-mail: adiis @ mail.telepac.pt<BR>

Fax: ++.351.1.8681593
