<head>
<title>Euskadi Information - Meet Euskal Herria</title>
</head>

<body>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="top"></a>
<table>
<tr>
<td><img align=left width=210 height=120 src="/~euskadi/layout/ei_logo2.gif">
</td>
<td align=center>
<font size=5><b>EUSKADI INFORMATION
<br>
Meet Euskal Herria</b></font>
<tt>
<p>
<i></i></font></tt></center>
<br>
</td>
</table>

<img align=middle src="/~euskadi/layout/l_rainb.gif">
<br>
<font size=2>
Text from a short booklet published by Herri Batasuna.
</font>
<hr>
<p>

<img align=left src="/~euskadi/archive/pictures/ei_001.gif">
<h2>You are in a different country</h2>
You know our Basque Country (Euskal Herria or Euskadi in Basque language) because of its cooking, its San Fermin fiestas... or perhaps because you've heard of the 1937 bombing of Gernika or nowadays because of the armed protest actions.
<p>
Now you have a good chance to get to know it from a different perspective. This sheets would like to point out some aspects of a country you know only little  about or you plan to visit once.
<p>

<h2>The Basque Country, a country divided in three parts</h2>
The Basque Country has a surface of 20'000 sqkm. Here live about 3 million people and the unemployment rate is around 25 %.
<p>
It has six historical teritories: Araba (capital Gasteiz-Vitoria), Bizkaia (capital Bilbo) and Gipuzkoa (capital Donostia-San Sebastián) belong to the Spanish State; Lapurdi (capital Baiona) and Zuberoa (capital Maule) to the French State. Nafarroa itself is split between both states, with one capital on each side of the border: Iruñea-Pamplona and Donibane Garazi-St. Jean Pied de Port.
<p>
In spite of its ancient culture and linguistic unity, the Basque Country lacks unitarian institutions. The North is integrated, together with Béarn, in the Département des Pyrénées Atlantiques (French State), not having any kind of autonomy. The South is divided into two different autonomic communities: Navarre and the Basque Autonome Community (Vascongadas).
<p>

<h2>The oldest language in Europe</h2>
The Basque language is one of the oldest in Europe, together with Finish and Hungarian, since they are the only ones spoken before the arrival of the Indoeuropeans (four thousand years ago) that are still alive.
<p>
It is spoken by about 24 % of the people in the Basque Country, with great differences between territories. The reason for this is that its use and knowledge is voluntary, while Spanish and French are compulsory.
<p>
People's effort to keep Euskara alive gathers thousands of people in demonstrations and events (fiestas) in support of the teaching for adults (AEK), the ikastolas (Basque schools) or the newspaper in Basque (Egunkaria).
<p>

<h2>The Ikurriña: our symbol </h2>
<img align=right src=/~euskadi/archive/pictures/ikurr.gif width=150>
The 14th July 1994 the ikurriña has met its 100th anniversary; from being the ensign under which the basque fighters fought in the Civil War, it has beecome our national flag.
<p>

<h2>History of a resistance</h2>
In 1512 the Kingdom of Navarra was conquered by the Castillian troops. Since them, Euskadi is divided between the Spanish and French States.
<p>
The Northern area (Lapurdi, Low Navarra and Zuberoa) kept their institutions until the French Revolution in 1789, time at which they were abolished with great resistance on the basque side.
<p>
In the South, the Court of Navarra gathered for the last time in 1829, just before the first Carlist war. These wars meant the loss of our institutions, laws and customs. For many years, gernika had been the emblem of the Basques, being a small town in which the representatives of the basque institutions had promised to defend the basque identity before a legendary oaktree.
<p>
<center>
<img src="/~euskadi/archive/pictures/gernika2.jpg" width=400 height=180>
</center>
<p>
In 1937 the fascist general Franco ordered to bomb this town on a market day. He wanted to destroy our identity and give a warning punishment. The following dictature until 1975 signified one of the most systematic and brutal repression periods for the Basque Country in its long history. Despite of the large number of victims and the prohibition of the basque language and culture, the idea of freedom and selfdetermination could never be killed. The permanent resistance lead 1959 finally to the formation of the armed organisation ETA (Euskadi Ta Askatasuna - Basque Country and Freedom) and the Basque National Liberation Movement.
<p>

<h2>Self-Determination: A denied right</h2>
In 1978, when the Spanish State adopted a Constitution which would rule its destiny, the basques rejected it by majority. The reason for this rejection was very simple: Madrid didn't want to recognize one of the most elementary rights, considered as legitimate by the UN: the Right to Self-Determination.
<p>
The Autodetermination has always been a pending subject in our country. In Euskal Herria the social outcry in favour of the Autodetermination has been increased with a resolution adopted by two majority patriotic trade unions - ELA and LAB - on the occasion of the Aberri Eguna (Day of the Basque Country), proclaiming that the key for getting peace and the freedom in Euskal Herria resides in the consecution of this right.
<p>

<h2>Madrid and Paris respond with sheer repression</h2>
The constant answer to the basque demands for democracy and and sovereignty is still sheer and hard repression. Did you know...
<ul>
<li>... that there are more than 600 people imprisoned for political reasons, scattered in more than 100 jails in both France and Spain, about 50 people deported in America and Africa and more than two thousands exiled?
<img align=left src="/~euskadi/archive/pictures/ei_004.jpg">
<li>... that while Amnesty International and the UN are reporting cases of torture - there were 267 cases verified by AI during 1994 - in the Spanish State, the Spanish "Justice" pardons and even decorates the torturers?
<li>... that during 1994, 733 persons were arrested in Euskal Herria by different Security Corps - Spanish and French Police, Guardia Civil and Basque Autonomous Police - and that, because of their repressive action, at least two persons have died in the basque streets?
<li>... that the tortured and calcinated bodies of the refugees Lasa and Zabala, who were kidnapped by the GAL, were found 12 years after their murder, and that the Spanish Security Corps kidnapped their dead bodies and repressed cruelly their families and friends, refusing to them the right to bury them in dignity?
<li>... that the Spanish Security Corps, including the Guardia Civil and the Army's information service (CESID), are implicated in the creation of the GAL ("Antiterrorist Liberation Groups"), an abbreviation under which the dirty war of the Spanish State against the Basque people is covered?
<li>... that this dirty war resulted to the murder of two Herri Batasuna members of the Spanish Parliament - Santi Brouard and Josu Muguruza - and 27 refugees?
<li>... that many charges of the spanish government, security and army corps, up to Barrionuevo, the former Minister of Interior, have been accused of promoting the GAL and having used the "reserved founds" (destinated to finance the dirty war) for personal enrichment?
<li>... that after the death of Javi Gorostiza on June 1995, ten more Basque political prisoners died because of the life conditions in the spanish and french jails?
<li>... that, in 1994 alone, 116 unsubmissive young people were arrested, and actually about 300 are still imprisonned, their only crime being that they don't want to serve in a foreign army and that they support the abolition of all military structures?
<li> And, and, and ...
</ul>
Do you understand now perhaps, why the Basque people wants and needs getting the autodetermination, for finally deciding of their own, how they want to build up their future in peace, freedom and solidarity with all other peoples over the world...?
<p>

<hr>
<p>
<h2>Do you want to know more about?</h2>
Read our background informations and detailed news, read what are the propositions for starting with a political dialogue that could lead to a peaceful solution of the conflict, read about our culture and history... Read also an introduction to our <a href="/euskadi/english/e_einfo.htm">alternative information project</a> on the Web. And tell other people about it.
<p>
<hr>

