<HEAD>
<title>De Anarchistische Ekonomische Gemeenschap</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<hr noshade>
<center><h1>Anarchist Economic<br> 
Community</h1>
</center>
<hr noshade>
<center><b>
<a href="#dyn">The framework of AEG</a> |
<a href="#tuin">The Garden Group</a> |
<a href="#voed">The Food Collective</a> |<br>
<a href="#volk">'Volkskeuken'</a> |
<a href="#info>The info-kitchen</a> |
<a href="#kok">The Mobile Action-Kitchen</a> |
</b></center>
<hr noshade>
<p>
<font size=4><b>T</b></font>he anarchist economic community (AEG) was founded in 1992 
in Ghent, Belgium, from a mutual feeling of
<i>'dissatisfaction with the current economical system'</i>. Although not
the only group with a likewise concept, there was a choice for a different
aproach. <b>From an anarchist background came the choice for forms of 
economic selfsufficiency, selfsupport and the logistical support of other
like-minded groups.</b>
<p><font size=4><b>W</b></font>e knew that a lot of people were bored with the classical forms of
organisation en we looked for more concrete, more practical
ways of resistance. We still saw the importance of actions and the 
distribution of informatiom as very important, but our alternative -
creating our own economical system - became an experiment on itself. This
concept had a lot of support from the beginning on. The anarchist and
radical ecological movement was our breeding ground. The rest of the 
capitalist world our target group.
<p><font size=4><b>N</b></font>ow, a couple of years later, AEG became a network
of workgroups, who on their own terms, each try to establish one of the
goals we set for ourselves at the start. AEG functions a 
collective and meeting place for actiongroups and
anarchist organisations.


<hr>
<a name="dyn"><h3>The complex and dynamic framework of AEG</h3></a>
<hr>
<p><font size=4><b>A</b></font>EG itself 
as an organisation plays only a secondary role. Since
the beginning the focus was on the <b>workgroups</b>, who on their
turn had their own <b>autonomous</b> character. In reality  
there are much common grounds en also on a juridical level there
are a couple of specific needs that demanded cooperation.
A non-profit structure was set up to regularize 
the activities and the workgroups; and AEG functioned mainly as
a communication channnel, as an administrative 'center' and as a 
financial support group. We emphasize that AEG is a network of
souvereign groups and we want it to stay that way.
<p><font size=4><b>E</b></font>very tree months the workgroups meet to discuss 
common problems and to solve them on a basicdemocratic way. We inform 
ourselves about
the way things work within the groups. The forming of new groups or 
dissolving of non-working group also happens during this meeting.
This is our only collective decision making organ. This means
that all important decisions are made within the framework of the 
groups. A healthy principle, we consider.

<p><font size=4><b>I</b></font>f it's financial necessary groups support each other. In that
way solidarity between autonomous groups becomes very important. The 
workgroups also finance our joint activities. 

<p><font size=4><b>T</b></font>o stimulate discussion between the workgroups and the outside
world, we distribute a <b>newsletter</b> every six weeks. Repports
of meetings, internal  discussions, somethimes very intense, form the
ideaal bed-lecture. This newsletter is proof to us that
AEG became a group with it's own typical character, while on the other hand 
we prefered a wide range of independant and heterogenous workgroups,
who support a common idea. This is our goal, but the initiative is
also in the hands of interested people. AEG has no membership, you 
just work along, whenever you feel like it.
<p><b><font size=4>C</font>heck out what type of groups are working within AEG:</b>

<hr>
<a name="tuin"><h3>THE GARDEN GROUP</h3>
<hr>
<p><font size=4><b>E</b></font>kological agriculture was high on the agenda of AEG since the
beginning. It was one of most realistic and concrete forms of
selfsupport. Not on a company level, but within the idea that everyone
can find him or herself a piece of land to produce vegetables and
fruit, in order to cope with the dependancy on the classical
poisoned food market, or the expensive biological sector. If you
do this as a group, it's not only cheaper but also more fun. A group like
this started off, and now a second piece of land is used for growing 
vegetables. There is more need for 'farmers', than for land, even in the 
middle of a city. For the moment the gardens only produce for the
people who work the land.
<br>
<hr>
<a name="voed"><h3>THE FOOD COLLECTIVE</h3></a>
<hr>
<p>
<font size=4><b>P</b></font>roduction of 
your own food may be within reach of a few people,
but most of us are depending upon the classical market and
distribution system. Also on this level a group started working. The
distribution of biological food, produced in a social and ecological 
way, in our own hands, is possible, so we've found out. Lots 
of examples in Holland, and even in our own country strengthened us in 
the opinion that it could be economical interesting to start
a group of consumers, who buy directly from the wholesaler or  
farmer. In Ghent the 'VOKO' has about 100 'clients', who make orders every 
tree months, of rice, flowers, beans,... 
The food is bought mostly from a wholesaler whose ideas are close to
that of AEG.
<p><font size=4><b>A</b></font>lso our other groups buy products from this group. This is for
us the only way to make biological food affordable for the 'poorer'. 
Consumer is a word we don't like. Our main goal is to let people
participate in the food collective, putting down the borders between
the producer and the unknowing consumer, and letting people decide 
themselves. Pressure upon cooperaters will force people to start a
second collective, and maybe even a third in Ghent. Decentralisation 
and distribution of work is absolutely  necessary to run a collective like 
this. 
<hr>
<a name="volk"><h3>DE VOLKSKEUKEN</h3></a>
<hr>
<p><font size=4><b>T</b></font>his one doesn't 
translate easily (maybe 'peoples kitchen' comes
close). 'De Volkskeuken' is one of the oldest projects within AEG and
even existed before AEG. The main point is to bring people together,
and by cooking and eating together create an informal meeting place
between groups and individuals. People in the movement know each other from
meetings and demonstrations, but this doesn't necessary lead towards
a closer exchange. This 'Volkskeuken' grew out to a weekly meeting
of people who do not necesseraly participate in the movement, and a
lot of projects and new contacts grew out of this initiative. 

<p><font size=4><b>E</b></font>very week people cook (an wash dishes of course)  a vegetarian 
meal for about thirty people. The food is very cheap, though
the intention is not charity or a restaurant. The people make their 
own 'Volkskeuken'. A couple of volunteers keep an eye on things,
do the bar, and count the money. 

<hr>
<a name="info><h3>THE INFO-KITCHEN</h3></a>
<hr>
<p><font size=4><b>I</b></font>n the spring of '95 
the info-kitchen started as reaction on the 
'classic''Volkskeuken' (see above), where it isn't always clear if
people are coming to fil their stomach or to meet each other. The
surplus of the info-kitchen comes out of an informative lecture, or
discussion after the meal. Every week a steady group of people 
prepare a vegetarian meal, and put the emphasis on directed 
information and a debate culture. this proved to be a very 
succesful formula.
<p><font size=4><b>I</b></font>nformation and discussion within the anarchist or 
radical leftist movement, isn't always very refreshing. Magazines 
sometime come extremely late with their own version of current 
newsfacts, and discussions especially when they come out of the own movement
are sometimes avoided. Besides, AEG needs a political undertone, 
that is permanentely  developed. The subjects that are brought,
in different ways, try to stimulate this. A video followed by discussion,
an informative lecture with discussion or a plain debate, drew a lot
of people who missed thes type of events for a couple of years.
Concrete results of this initiative will be found back in the action movement
and a lot of people certainly remember the pleasant moments at the
bar afterwords.

<hr>
<a name="kok"><h3>THE MOBILE ACTION-KITCHEN</h3></a>
<hr>
<p><i><font size=4><b>" O</b></font>ur world 
nowadays is orchestrated by a couple of gigantic
villains. Multinationals and political and economic systems,
that make the common people sick, are making an enormous mess, without
much resistance. Hunger, pollution, poverty and other abuses are
the direct result of this. Also in our own lives we are
put down by the influence of these mighty giants. 
<p><font size=4><b>B</b></font>ut there are people who want to try in a different way and 
from the idea of selfsupport en selfsufficiency try the give
shape to their own lives. Our mobile kitchen 'Kokkerellen' is
part of this. We want to support people and groups in establishing
a different way of live en to offer an inspiring alternative to
our normal dealing with food..."</i> A part of a leaflet from 
the mobile action-kitchen; in true AEG-style.
<p><font size=4><b>A</b></font>gain a kitchen that is introduced, but this time with it's own
specific goal. In the same spirit of the garden group en the
food collective en the 'Volkskeukens', the mobile kitchen searches
for an ecological and biological alternative. Vegetarian meals
are the mean that is used to let the person who eats it, reflect about
his or her consumerism. The people who eat our food are member
of actiongroups are participants in big meetings who have no
time nor means to cook themselves.
<p><font size=4><b>K</b></font>okkerellen is not a restaurant, though.  When
they go cooking somewhere, they want to participate in the whole and
the other way round, they also expect help from the people cutting
vegetables. Kokkerellen has the infrastructure, the food and the people 
to provide cooking.
<p><font size=4><b>T</b></font>he price depends on the situation and the number of
people. The kitchen depends fully on volunteers. The bit of profit
that is made, is invested in new material, transport and costs
for the organising.
<br>
<br>

