<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>VG-8</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUNDCOLOR="ffffff" TEXT="#000000"  background="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/logoback.gif">
<img align=right src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/roland.gif">
<img align=top src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/vg8.jpg">
<h1>V-Guitar System VG-8</h1>
<h2>Experience the next generation of guitar</h2><hr>
<h3>Enhancing the guitar's natural
expressiveness</h3>

The guitar has a natural expressiveness
that surpasses many of the unavoidable
limitations of keyboards and other instru
ments. Because of the tactic nature of the
strings and fingerboard, the guitar brings
out the individualism of each payer and
offers a range of expressive features that
are unique to the instrument.
<p>
The VG-8 augments these inherent
characteristics by combining the power of
digital technology with the guitar's unique
tactile qualities. The result is a revolution
in performance and sound creation, taking
the guitar to a new level of expression.
<hr>
<h3>Signal processing designed especially for the guitar</h3>
The VG-8 can be controlled with virtually
any guitar by using the Roland GK-2A
divided pickup. The GK-2A installs easily
on the body of most steel-stringed electric
or acoustic guitars, turning any ordinary
guitar into a completely new instrument
with extraordinary expressive potential.
<p>
This unique divided pickup detects the
vibrations of each string individually and in
realtime. Roland's advanced DSP technol
ogy enables instantaneous tracking and
processing of string vibrations, resulting in
an entirely new sound output. And since processing is conducted on the actual
waveform created by the string's vibration,
all of the original expressive nuances of
the performer's playing style remain intact.
<p>
The GK-2A divided pickup enables a variety
of polyphonic capabilities. For instance,
pitch shift can be applied to individual
strings, giving you instant open tunings
without touching your tuning pegs.
Or you can switch to an authentic 12-string
sound (ie. bottom four strings are octaved
while the top two strings are doubled).
Each string can be panned individually to
provide a rich stereo image or a unique
stereo environment. Polyphonic distortion
lets you play heavily distorted power
chords with distinctive harmony.
<hr>
<h3>A new approach to sound creation</h3>

Combining advanced digital sound
processing with the expressive capabilities
of the guitsr requires a totally new approach.
Roland has invented just
such an approach with
COSM (Composite Object
Sound Modeling).
COSM is an object-oriented
technique of sound
creation that its you
build sounds in a logical,
yet musical way.
Once you've created a
new sound, the VG-8 lets
you add the final contour
with high-quality onboard
digital effects and
equalization.
<hr>
<h3>Two distinctive modes</h3>

The VG-8's innovative
COSM technology
consists of two modes:
Variable Guitar Modeling
(VGM) and Harmonic
Restructure Modeling
(HRM).
<ol>
<h4><li>Variable Guitar Modeling (VGM)</h4>

The VG-8's VGM mode enables you to
emulate classic guitar sounds by combining
various modeling techniques. For instance,
electronic modeling reproduces sound
charactaristics associated with electronic
circuits such as vacuum tubes or transis-
tors, while magnetic modeling reproduces
the characteristics of magnetic compo-
nents, such as pickups, transformers and
speakers. By combining these different
elements, you can instantly reproduce the
total sound of virtually any guitar and
amplifier, no matter which guitar or amp
you are physically playing.
<p>
Imagine being able to select "virtual"
pickups that let you instantly change
from a hard-rocking humbucker to a
smooth, vintage single coil to a piezo.
You can change the position of the
virtual pickup, placing it anywhere
between the bridge and the nut.
You can even "virtually" place it right
on the neck!
<p>
<h4><li>Harmonic Restructure Modeling (HRM)</h4>
HRM is a modeling technique that lets
you create completely new sounds,
while retaining the guitar's unique
expressiveness. HRM isolates the
complex vibration of a guitar string,
letting you add, delete or intensify
certain harmonics to create fantastic
new sounds, from synthesized tex
tures to brass or woodwind-like tones.
<p>
Unlike a MIDI guitar synthesizer,
which uses pitch and level information
to trigger a sound generator, the VG-8
punches the actual waveform creat
ed by each string's vibration. This is
the key to the VG-8's incredible ex
pressivenesss. Everything from picking
dynamics to fret harmonics to the
subtle sonic changes of string bends is
faithfully reproduced, thus preserving
the feel of your individual playing style.
</ol>
<hr>

<h3>High-quality effects and EQ</h3>

To add the finishing touches to your
V-Guitar sound creations, professional-quality effects and EQ are built-in,
making the VG-8 a completely self-
contained guitar sound production
system. These processors work just
like the outboard gear and EQs in a
conventional guitar system. Three
types of modulation are provided,
including chorus, phase, tremolo and
hex panning, as well as delay and
reverb. In addition, a high-quality EQ is
provided with high, mid and low bands.
<hr>
<h3>Easy operation designed for guitarists</h3>

The VG-8 V-Guitar System is designed
with the guitarist in mind, featuring a
floor-pedal design with Bank/Group
pedals for easy sound selection,
an alpha dial for quick parameter
changes and even a built-in tuner.
Rather than using numeric functions
or complicated technology, the
V-Guitar employs an object-oriented
interface, with icons that make
sound modeling and selection easy
and intuitive. Operations are further
facilitated by the large, backlit LCD.
<p>
The VG-8 comes with 64 preset
Patches that feature everything from
classic guitar/amp sounds to extra-
ordinary synthesizer-type effects.
In addition, 64 user Patches are
available for storing your own sounds,
which can be instantly accessed using
the Bank/Group pedals. A headphone
jack is also provided for private
practice sessions.
<hr>
<h2>Composite Object Sound Modeling (COSM)</h2>

<b>Once a musical instrument generates sound vibration, it reaches human ears through
various mediating objects. Each object significantly affects the sound. The material
and configuration of the instrument, the electric/electronic/magnetic amplifying
system, the air and the reverberation of the room all affect the final sound.
<p>
Sound modeling, the latest DSP technology, "virtually" reconstructs these objects.
Roland's innovative Composite Object Sound Modeling (COSM) uses the advantages
of multiple modeling methods and succeeds in accurately emulating existing sounds,
as well as producing sounds that have never before been physically created.</b>
<hr>
<h5>The guitar, as we know it today, is the result of several hundred years of development. Since the early days of guitar production, artisans have
experimented with different woods, strings and acoustical designs. Over the course of time modern manufacturing techniques were introdoced
and new innouations emerged. Through trial and error, the guitar has slowly evolued into the instrument that we knouv so well today.<br>
A milestone in the history of the guitar came with the addition of a pickup and an amplifier. This was a deuelopment that reuolutionized not
only the instrument, but music itself. Amplification provided increased volume as well as increased expressive capabilities through overdrive,
sustain and other tonal characteristics associated with various types of pickups and amplifiers.<br>
Now Roland adds a neuv chapter in the euolution of the guitar with the VG 8 V Guitar System. Using Roland's latest advances in OSP (Digital
Signal Processing/ technology, the VG-8 offers an entirely new approach to creating great guitar sounds. 1Ilot a synthesizer, not an effects unit,
the VG-8 V-Guitar System is a totally unique concept in the history of the guitar.</h5>

<hr>
<a href="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/index.html"><img align=bottom src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/home.gif"></a> 
</BODY></HTML>


























