<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>e-64</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUNDCOLOR="ffffff" TEXT="#000000"  background="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/logoback.gif">
<img align=right src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/e-mu.gif">
<img align=top src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/e64.jpg">
<p>
<h1>e-64 64-voice digital sampling system</h1>
<hr><p>
<b>The e-64 64-Voice Digital Sampling System delivers a new level of
      power, memory, voices and functionality to users in a variety of
        performance and audio production environments.  Boasting an
            incredible 64 voices of polyphony and up to 64 megabytes
                       (MB) of sample memory, e-64 carries the E-mu
                                   tradition of delivering superb audio
                                        resolution as well as powerful,
                                                    innovative features.</b>


<hr>
<h2>Audio Quality</h2>
        Through the integration of E-mu's latest-generation proprietary
   DSP technologies and cutting-edge software tools, e-64 delivers
   audio quality, and related functionality that sets new standards of
   performance and value.<br>
        The e-64 features true 16-bit resolution for the purest possible
   digital audio reproduction.  All e-64 units also boast superb analog
   sampling capabilities via two channels of 128x oversampling
   sigma/delta conversion.  Discrete 18-bit digital-to-analog converters,
   or DACS, per output channel provide for increased headroom and the
   assurance that e-64's high audio quality, and accuracy are translated to
   the analog domain.<br>
        The e-64 also allows for virtually distortionless pitch transposition
   over an incredible 10-octave range. aliasing, imaging, clock noise and
   other digital artifacts are eliminated by maintaining a constant,
   yet selectable, sample rate of either 44.1kHz or 48kHz, regardless
   of transposition.

<p>

  <h2> Voicing and Memory   </h2>                                  
        The e-64 features 64-voicc polyphony
     facilitating complex multi-timbral musical            
   composition and effects tracks-as well as 
   dense multilavcr stereo sounds-without a
   paralyzing reduction in polyphony. While 
   the e-64 is the industry's only 64-voice
   sampler, it is also incredibly affordable on                  
   a per-voice basis.<br>                 
        The e-64 will accept up to 64MB of
   standard SIMM sample RAM.  This significant amount of sample
   memory provides for a huge palate of sounds to be loaded and
   accessible at any one time.  The e-64 is also designed to accommodate
   up to 16MB of Flash sample memory.  Nonvolatile Flash memory
   provides for a selection of user-definable sounds to be permanently
   stored and instantly accessible, without the need to load them each
   time the e-64 is powered up.

<p>
<h2>Audio Sculpting</h2>
        The e-64 is also armed with a comprehensive palate of audio
   "sculpting" tools.  Once raw audio data has been captured, e-64
   allows for extensive manipulation of the data via powerful sample
   editing functions and DSP tools.<br>
        The e-64's new icon-based 240 x 64 graphic user interface,
   Coupled with an ergonomically designed front-panel control surface,
   makes operation fast and intuitive.  A standard ASCII keyboard
   interface further streamlines e-64 operation by providing remote
   control of all functions from an optional ASCII keyboard.  This
   optional keyboard also greatly reduces time while naming banks,
   presets and samples.

  <h2> Synthesis Capabilities</h2>
        While e-64's 64 6th-order digital resonant filters (including a
   wide variety of selectable filter types) allow for further modifications
   of samples, they are also invaluable in creating stunning synthesis
   effects using samples as oscillators, or raw data.  The e-64 combines
   these powerful digital filters with an array of traditional analog
   synthesizer functionality, including a variety of "virtual" patch cords.
   These patch cords form a Matrix Modulation system that allows users
   to link dozens of modulation sources, processors and destinations
   together, in any conceivable order, to create startling synthesis
   effects.  Hence, the characteristics and principles of traditional analog
   synthesis has been captured in e-64's 21st Century implementation.

  <h2> Integrated Functionality</h2>
        A variety of features have been integrated into the e-64 which
   provide greater convenience and efficiency during the unit's operation.
   Using the e-64's high-resolution display as a front end, graphic
   waveform editing can be accomplished without the need for an
   external computer and software package.  The "re-sample while play"
   function provides for the internal recording of the e-64's output
   program without an external recording device.  Finally, integrated
   browse and search functions deliver the ability to manage sound
   libraries without an external librarian package-using the optional
   ASCII keyboard.

   <h2>Sound Library</h2>
        E-mu's renowned sample library encompasses nearly every
   musical instrument on earth, as well as a mind-boggling array
   of Sound effects.  The e-64 is fully compatible with EIV, Elllx,
   ESI-32 and Emax II libraries of 16-bit digital samples and the Akai
   S1OOO/1100 sound libraries, via SCSI, complete with key mapping
   and other parameters.  With support by
                           the industry's leading third-party sound
                           developers, there are over 50 gigabytes of
                           e-64 compatible sound libraries available on
                           CD-ROM with additions being made constantly

<h2>Mass Storage</h2>

      Dual 50-pin SCSl-connectors offer compatibility, with a variety
 of mass storage devices, including external hard disk, CD-ROM,
 Syquest removable hard disk and Magneto/Optical drives.  Any of
 these storage devices can be used to access the e-64 library,.  An
 internal 1GB drive is also available as an e-64 option.

<h2> Input/Output</h2>

      For mixing, e-64 delivers output flexibility with eight polyphonic
 outputs.  Of course, for completely digital environments, e-64's
 AES/EBU digital I/0 affords users the ability, to never Ieave the digital
 domain with their work.  Digital audio output can be routed directly
 to digital recorders or processors with compatible digital I/0 such
 as hard disk recording systems.  The e-64's AES/EBU digital I/0
 also conforms to the consumer digital I/0 format (S/PDIF), for
 the added convenience of compatibility, with a variety of other input
 and output devices.

<hr>
<h2>Sample Editing Functions</h2>
<ul>
<li>Loop
<li>Truncate
<li>Taper
<li>Cut, Copy and Paste
<li>Sample Calculator
<li>Sample Integrity
<li>Stereo <-> Mono
<li>Swap Left <->Right
<li>DC Filter
<li>Undo
</ul>
<h2>DSP Features</h2>
<ul>
<li>Time Compression/Expansion
<li>Pitch Change
<li>Compressor
<li>Parametric EQ
<li>Gain Change
<li>Sample Rate Conversion
<li>Digital Tuning
<li>Reverse Selection
<li>Doppler
<li>Exciter
<li>Transform Multiplication
</ul>
<h2>Standard Features</h2>
<ul>
<li>64-voice polyphony
<li>up to 64MB sample memory
<li>64 6th-order digital resonant filters/EQ (including a variety of selectable filter types)
<li>EIV, EIIIx, ESI-32, and EMAX II library compatibility via SCSI
<li>onboard library "search" function
<li>ASCII keyboard interface
<li>re-sample while play
<li>load while play
<li>audition sample from disc
<li>240 x 64 icon-based graphic user-interface
<li>onboard graphic waveform editing
<li>virtually distortionless pitch transposition over a 10-octave range
<li>discrete 18-bit digital-to-analog converters (DACs) per channel
<li>128x oversampling sigma/delta conversion
<li>eight polyphonic outputs
<li>AES/EBU digital I/O
<li>dual 50-pin SCSI ports
</ul>
<hr>
