<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>DMT8</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUNDCOLOR="ffffff" TEXT="#000000"  background="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/logoback.gif">
<img align=right src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/fostex.gif">
<img align=top src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/dmt8.jpg">
<p>
<h1>DMT-8</h1>
<hr>
<h2>YOUR 'WISH LIST' MULTITRACKER</h2>
<p>
<h2><blink>We're happy to announce thet the DMT-8 dropped in price to 58.000 BFr.</blink></h2>
If someone asked you to design your ideal multitracker you'd no doubt have a pretty good
idea of what it should include, what it should look like and how it should perform.
<p>

<h2>DIGITAL QUALITY</h2>

First, we suspect, on your 'wish list' would be ultra high quality recording.  The type of
recording only available in professional studios.  Digital recording without compression or
compromise.
<p>

<h2>8 TRACKS</h2>

And 8-tracks would be nice.  After all, 4 tracks might have been OK for Mr Pepper and the
boys but once you've laid a few vocals and a guitar part or two it leaves precious little room for
much else.  No, it would have to have 8 tracks.  With editing.
The ability to cut and paste sections instantly with an undo feature should do it.
On the mixing side, you'd no doubt want something that's quiet, flexible, with great EQ and lots
of inputs.  Oh, and plenty of input options on mixdown.

<p>
<h2>
EASY INTEGRATION</h2>

You'd also want a machine which integrates easily into the Midi environment, generating
Miditimecode without losing tracks, and transport controllable via a software sequencer.
Finally you'd probably want all this in a great looking box, which is a snap to use and at a price
not much above conventional analogue multitrackers.  Allow us to introduce your 'wish list' -
The new Fostex DMT-8 Digital Multitracker.
<p>

<h2>TRUE CD QUALITY RECORDING DIRECT TO HARD DISK</h2>
Some digital recorders ask you to make do with 12-bit recording, some with compression,
some even expect you to accept inferior sample rates.
Professionals don't accept these 'cost cutters' so why should you?  The fact of the matter is
that CDquality recording demands full linear 16-bit resolution digital to analogue conversion at
a sample rate of 44.I kHz.
A specification which the Fostex DMT-8 meets with ease.  With its own 32-bit RISC (Reduced
Instruction Set Computer)CPU, this incredible machine gives 8 tracks of CD-quality recording
and instant monitoring playback, to and from an internal 540 MB Quantum hard drive.
<p>

<h2>EVERYTHING YOU NEED</h2>

Nice touches include 4 track simultaneous recording, cut, copy, paste audio editing with undo
and instant monitoring, full MTC (Midi Time Code) sync facilities, 6 memory locations for
'jumping' to songs or sections, a handy dual-function jog/shuttle wheel providing digital scrub
without pitch change, Auto Locate to ABS 0 and ABS End, archiving via DAT, and individual
channel outputs.
Yet with all this sophistication it's incredibly easy to use, adding new meaning to that often
mis-used phrase "tapeless studio".
<p>

<h2>EASY RECORDING</h2>

If the CD-quality of the audio impresses, the wealth of recording and sync facilities built-in to the
DMT-8 can only amaze.
<p>

<h2>AUTO FUNCTIONS</h2>

The digital recorder has 6 programmable time memories. Located on easy to access buttons,
these memories allow you to copy audio between two points and paste to a third. In addition,
these memories offer full locate functions including Auto Locate, Auto Return/Play and Auto
Punch In/Out between two points.
Auto Locate to ABS 0 and ABS END are also available.
<p>

<h2>PUNCH IN/OUT</h2>

Re-recording sections or overdubs is a snap thanks to an auto punch in/out facility providing
full rehearsal or recording modes at the touch of a button.
<p>

<h2>SYNC AND MIDI</h2>

Yes there's Midi Time Code. (But unlike most multitracks, you don't lose a track).  And yes it's
possible to control the transport functions from your favourite software sequencer.  But get this.
The beauty of highly portable, allin-one multitrackers is that they offer the possibility to record
almost anywhere.
Sounds great in theory, but when you try to add sequenced keyboard parts to that nifty acoustic
guitar riff you recorded using the natural reverb of your mate's bathroom, it all comes apart.
Not so with the clever DMT-8.  Having a built-in metronome with eleven signature types, full tempo
control and Midi clock output with Song Position Pointer means 'location' recordings can be
perfectly matched to a sequencer at a later date.
All you have to do is play in time.
<p>

<h2>TYPICAL FOSTEX USEABILITY</h2>

You don't need to be a computer wiz to get the best out of the DMT-8 or to gain access to its
wealth of features. To perform a given task, say to save data to a DAT drive, only requires you
to follow a simple 'question' and 'answer' step by step routine.  All of which are clearly shown in
the FL tube 'display centre' window in plain English.
<p>

<h2>'FEELS' LIKE TAPE</h2>

The ease of use also extends to the transport - here is a digital hard disk recorder which really
'feels' like a tape machine.  There are familiar functions such as 5x fast forward and rewind in play
mode with full audio monitoring as well as conventional wind and rewind buttons which "spool"
at 30x normal speed.
<p>

<h2>DIGITAL MULTITRACKING</h2>

Having the ability to record 8 Ttracks of CD-quality audio demands a mixer of class-leading
flexibility and the DMT-8 doesn't disappoint, it excels with an ultraquiet board perfectly designed
for the task in hand.
<p>

<h2>FLEXIBILITY</h2>

Being an in-line format mixer, it offers tremendous flexibility with many inputs and options,
especially on mix-down.  In-line technology means each channel has two inputs.  When track
laying the main input would be used for incoming instruments with the secondary input (SUB)
used to monitor recorded tracks with full pan and level control.
However it is in remix where the DMT-8 really delivers, offering control over a staggering 22
inputs.  This gives you the opportunity to mixdown the 8 recorded tracks along with 14 channels
of sequenced music without the need to resort to the additional submixers.  And with S/PDIF LR
outputs you can go straight to DAT in the digital domain.
<p>

<h2>CLOSE FOCUS EQ</h2>
The EQ section is again an area in which Fostex's experience and class-leading design shows
through.  Not for the DMT-8 basic tone controls, but sophisticated, yet easy to use parametric
equalisation which enables you to tailor sounds exactly to your requirements: warm up vocals,
reduce bass drum slap, add sparkle to guitars, enhance the mid in horns - it's all possible.
Then there's the auxiliary sends.  Some multitracks tie you down to only adding effects whilst track
laying.  But in using dual-function AUX pots which can take their feed from either the main channel
input (post fader) or the sub input, the DMT-8 typically offers the flexibility of recording tracks 'wet'
or 'dry' and adding reverb and the like at mixdown.
<hr>
<a href="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/index.html"><img align=bottom src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/home.gif"></a> 
</BODY></HTML>














