Subject: Book: Netlearning-Teachers & Intern
Date: 17 Jun 1996 22:24:57 -0800 (PST)

From: Hilary Naylor  hnaylor@igc.org 
Subject: Book: Netlearning-Teachers & Internet

Date: Wed, 5 Jun 1996 22:03:22 -0400
From: listown@online.ora.com (O'Reilly & Associates ORA-NEWS Owner)
To: Multiple recipients of list  ora-news@online.ora.com 
Subject: "NetLearning" from O'Reilly

               NetLearning: Why Teachers Use the Internet
                  By Ferdi Serim & Melissa Koch
               292 pages; ISBN: 1-56592-201-8, $24.95 (US)

     We have just released this guide to the Internet for K-12
educators.  It is written by Ferdi Serim, founder of the Online
Internet Institute, and Melissa Koch, developer of the Global
Network Navigator's education site.

     NetLearning is the first Internet guide for teachers that uses
teachers' real-life stories to show how project-based,
technology-enhanced approaches aid learning.  The educators'
stories also serve as a guide for dealing with many of the
instructional, curricular, professional development,
administrative, and community issues that develop around
the use of the Internet in schools.

     We've posted an excerpt from NetLearning, "Being Creative With
the Technology," on the O'Reilly web site.  You can access it at
<a href=http://www.ora.com/info/netlearn>http://www.ora.com/info/netlearn</a>

     The table of contents includes:

       Chapter 1 -- Classroom Tales
       Chapter 2 -- Classroom Connections
       Chapter 3 -- Basic Internet Training
       Chapter 4 -- Students in the Internet Classroom
       Chapter 5 -- Teachers Creating Online Collaborations
       Chapter 6 -- The Innovative School
       Chapter 7 -- The Connected Community
       Chapter 8 -- Bringing it All Back Home

    The seeds for the online portion of the book already exist.
Started by Ferdi Serim and funded by the National Science Foundation,
the Online Internet Institute (<a href=http://www.oii.org>http://www.oii.org</a> is an online six-
to nine-week course where Internet-using educators, proponents of
systemic reform, and content-area experts form online collaborative
groups to 1) learn to use Internet tools better; 2) develop the process
of creating online lessons; and 3) create new forms of online lessons.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
This book and other O'Reilly products are available in the Americas,
Japan, Oceania, and Eastern Europe through bookstores, or directly from
the publisher (credit card orders 800-889-8969 in the US & Canada;
Email order@ora.com).  GSA # GS-02F-6095A. For a list of our
international distributors, access the Web and gopher servers listed
below.

O'Reilly's Catalog and Resource Center can be accessed on the Web at
<a href=http://www.ora.com/>http://www.ora.com/</a> or through gopher or telnet to gopher.ora.com
(telnet login: gopher)

For Information: Phone 707-829-0515 (800-998-9938 in US & Canada);
Fax 707-829-0104; Email info@ora.com; or write O'Reilly & Associates,
103A Morris St., Sebastopol, CA, 95472, USA.


-- 
Sara Winge    sara@ora.com
O'Reilly & Associates
103A Morris St., Sebastopol, CA 95472
707/829-0515, Fax 707/829-0104, <a href=http://www.ora.com/>http://www.ora.com/</a>

