So: U-hr
From: irainc@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: aihre.general
Subject: Urgent Action Alert-Iranian Refugee
Date: 28 Jun 1996 15:26:00 -0800 (PST)


June 28, 1996

URGENT ACTION ALERT
Fear of Deportation of more than 80 Iranian Asylum 
Seekers in Turkey

Last night around 1 a.m., Turkish security forces rounded up 
more than 80 Iranian asylum seekers who were still 
participating in a protest sit-in in Ankara staged in August 
1995. Ten adults were arrested in the office of the Human 
Rights Association where they have been staging a hunger 
strike since June 3. The rest of the people, including more than 
30 children, were rounded up from the office of the Freedom 
and Solidarity Party, the main site of the sit-in. The sit-in was 
staged to cancel the deportation orders and to urge the Ankara 
Branch of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees 
(UNHCR) to re-open the cases of the participants, who were 
denied a meaningful appeal after their refugee claims were 
rejected by the Office.

Turkish authorities have reportedly expressed their aim as only 
returning the participants to their prior towns of residence in 
Turkey. However, based on events happening prior to the round up, 
Iranian Refugees' Alliance is extremely concerned that these 
attacks is a precursor to actual deportation of all or part of the 
sit-in participants, which could subject them to persecution by 
the Iranian government.

Prior to this round up, on Friday June 21st, Karim Shahrashoub, a 
sit-in participant was arrested outside of the sit-in received a 
deportation order immediately after being returned to his town of 
prior residence. He was subsequently removed to the border town 
of Agri, where all deportees are taken prior to be forced across the 
border to Iran or being directly handed over to Iranian authorities.
In Iran, people who oppose or are suspected of opposing the 
government face serious human rights violations including torture 
and the death penalty. The sit-in protest have come to the attention 
of the Iranian authorities as a protest directed against this 
government and the Iranian authorities have openly expressed a 
hostile view against sit-in participants.

Iranian Refugees' Alliance asks all concerned organizations to 
send letters to the Turkish authorities and the UNHCR and:

- call for immediate clarification of Karim Shahrashoub's 
whereabouts, asking whether he is currently detained in Agri and if 
so ask for his immediate release.

- express concern over imminent deportation of the sit-in group and 
call for immediate assurances that none of the sit-in participants will 
be forcibly returned to Iran where they would face gross human 
rights violations.

- call for immediate extension of the sit-in participant's stay 
permits in Turkey by the Turkish authorities until a durable and safe 
solution is found. 

- call for a constructive response by the UNHCR towards the sit-in 
participants.

- point out that there are other safe and durable solutions which so 
far neither the Turkish authorities nor the UNHCR have considered 
such as Canada's Private sponsorship program and  Australia's 
refugee and humanitarian visa program.

- call for  immediate provisions by the Turkish Government and the 
UNHCR to utilize their resources and to facilitate resettlement of 
the sit-in participants by means of other solutions. 

- point out that after 11 months of an anguished life in the 
overcrowded site of the sit-in and despite the dismal living 
conditions, scattering the sit-in participants in various towns is 
inhumane and obstructive in finding a safe and durable solution for 
the group. 

Please send your letters immediately:


TO: TURKISH AUTHORITIES

Minister of the Interior:

Mr. Ulku Guney     [Salutation: Dear Minister]
Icisleri Bakanligi
Bakanliklar Ankara, Turkey
Fax: (90 312) 418 1795

Minister of the Foreign Affairs:

Emre Gonensay       [Salutation: Dear Minister]
Disisleri Bakanligi
06100 Ankara
Faxes: (90 312) 419 1547

TO: United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
Representative : Barry Rigby
UNHCR-Branch Office in Turkey
17 Abidin Daver Sokak Cankaya 
Ankara 06680 Turkey
phone: (90 312) 439 66 15-18 
Fax: (90 312)438 2702
email: turan@unhcr.tr 

copies to:

High Commissioner Sadako Ogata
UNHCR- Geneva Headquarters
Case Postale 2500, CH-1211 Geneva 2 
Depot  Switzerland
phone: (41-22) 739-8111  Fax: (41-22) 731-9546

Nicholas Dahrendors
UNHCR-Senior Regional Legal 
Adviser for Eastern & Central Europe
phone: (41-22) 739-8111  Fax: (41-22) 739-7332

Dennis MacNamara
UNHCR-Division of International 
Protection
phone: (41-22) 739-8111  Fax: (41-22) 731-9546


For more information please contact 

Iranian Refugees' Alliance, Inc.
Cooper Station P.O.Box 316 NY NY 10278-0316 USA
Tel/Fax: 212-260-7460   e-mail: irainc@igc.apc.org

or 

Human Rights Association-Ankara Branch (Insan Haklari Dernegi)
Bayindir 2 Sok. No. 38/8 Kizilay  Ankara Turkey
Tel: 90-312-433-7481    Fax: 90-312-435-7615
e-mail: IHD-ANK@info-ist.comlink.de     ne02- k@servis2.net.tr

^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
- - - - continued - - More Background Information - - - -
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

June 28, 1996
URGENT ACTION ALERT
Fear of Deportation of more than 80 Iranian Asylum Seekers 
in Turkey

^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
More Back ground Information
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

The general climate concerning protection of persons seeking 
asylum in Turkey has been a deteriorating one. Since November 
1994 after Turkish authorities announced new regulation for non-
Europeans requesting temporary asylum, the protection of all non-
European asylum seekers has been severely undermined. During 
1995, UNHCR reported that 42 Iranians who UNHCR recognized 
as refugees were subjected to forcible return by the Turkish 
authorities. In some cases, they were even accepted by a third 
country for resettlement. Based on reports received by Iranian 
Refugees' Alliance, the number of deportees who have not been 
recognized as refugees by the UNHCR or who have been returned 
at the border are several times more. 

The sit-in was staged in early August 1995 by close to 70 families 
(representing over 160 persons), under extremely desperate 
conditions. In late summer of 1995, dozens of asylum seekers were 
at once facing imminent deportation by the Turkish authorities, 
while the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees 
(UNHCR) Branch Office in Turkey continued to refuse a 
meaningful appeal procedure to the at-risk asylum seekers whose 
refugee claims have been rejected earlier by the UNHCR. The sit-in 
was staged to cancel the deportation orders and to urge the 
UNHCR to re-open the cases of the participants. 

This protest action has been widely publicized and has received 
wide support from Turkish groups and individuals and from all over 
the world. While this has so far been a convincing force for the 
Turkish authorities to reprieve the deportation orders in practice, 
both the Ankara Branch of the UNHCR and the Geneva 
Headquarters have continued to refuse any form of assistance to the 
sit-in participants. The agency has refused to afford the protesters a 
meaningful appeal (which according to international standards 
should at minimum include rights such as the being informed of the 
grounds for the rejection, obtaining legal advice and representation 
and to have a full and fair hearing; these rights have not existed in 
the UNHCR refugee determination procedure). Nor has the agency 
made any attempts to re-assess the claims of the participants based 
on their new condition or consider other humanitarian solutions for 
the group.

International organizations such as the Canadian Council for 
refugees, Jesuit Refugee Service and US Committee for Refugees 
(USCR) have appealed to both the Turkish government and 
UNHCR to seek a humanitarian resolution of the sit-in. In October 
1995 USCR visited Turkey. Based on testimonies presented to 
USCR by the sit-in participants, the organization has believed that 
many of the sit-in participants have credible claims. Moreover, 
USCR has been convinced that the sit-in would be perceived as an 
overt political act by the Iranian authorities, that the identities of the 
sit-in participants were known to the Iranian authorities, and that 
they did, consequently, have a well-founded fear of persecution 
upon return to Iran, not necessarily for acts committed while living 
in Iran, but for their activities in Turkey. 

During the past 11 months despite continuos threats to disperse and 
deport the sit-in participants, Turkish authorities have refrained 
from any actual actions against the group. In several occasions that 
the participants were arrested outside the site of the sit-in, they were 
released shortly after. So has been the case in two other occasions 
where the entire sit-in group was arrested by the police after staging 
demonstrations against the Iranian government. 

However, as of last week a new policy is enforced. On Friday, June 
21st, 6 sit-in participants were arrested by the police while grocery 
shopping for the group at a nearby store and were forcibly returned 
to their former towns of residence. Five of the apprehended 
managed to escape and return to the site of the sit-in in Ankara. But 
one participant is reported to have received a deportation order right 
after arrival in his town of prior residence. He was subsequently 
removed to the border town of Agri, where all deportees are taken 
prior to be forced across the border to Iran or being directly handed 
over to Iranian authorities.

Although diplomatic relations between Turkey and Iran have 
deteriorated in the past several months, the number of deportations 
has increased. Recently, Amnesty International has expressed fears 
that Turkey may be expelling Iranian asylum-seekers and refugees 
to improve relations under a security agreement with Iran which 
reportedly includes the reciprocal exchange of opposition activists. 
In April 1995, a Turkish newspaper reported that news on 
reciprocal exchange of P.K.K. members residing in Iran and Iranian 
dissident asylum seekers residing in Turkey was officially 
confirmed by an Iranian official. There are strong evidence 
indicating high level of cooperation in exchanging dissidents 
between the two countries regardless of diplomatic relationships.

In Iran, people who oppose or are suspected of opposing the 
government risk serious human rights violations including torture 
and the death penalty. In one publicized commentary broadcasted 
by the Islamic Republic News Agency in February 1996, the 
Iranian deputy foreign minister for Asia-Pacific affairs, has referred 
to the sit-in participants as "a group of hypocrite grouplets" and has 
strongly protested to the Turkish government regarding the 
unacceptable activities and anti-Islamic measures taken by the sit-in 
group, referring to a demonstration staged by the sit-in group 
against the Islamic Republic of Iran on the occasion of the 17th 
anniversary of the victory of the Islamic revolution. In April 1995, 
Dr. Saeed Rejaie, an Assembly representative of the Tehran regime 
in reply to questions asked by a Turkish reporter referred to the sit-
in participants as "subversive traitors". 

In response to the risks faced by the sit-in participants, where 
possible, groups and individuals have offered viable opportunities 
for a safe and durable solution. Currently more than a dozen cases 
have been privately sponsored by Canadian churches. They are 
waiting for an assessment of their applications by the Canadian 
refugee program. If recognized as refugees, they will be resettled in 
Canada as privately sponsored refugees. Elligible private sponsors 
in Australia have offered assistance to sit-in participants as support 
to their humanitarian visa applications. All of the sit-in participants 
have pending or unresolved visa applications with the Australian 
embassy. The barrier of obtaining permission from the Turkish 
authorities to exit Turkey has been a negative factor in the success 
of these resettlement programs. In addition, while these program's 
operate independent of the UNHCR, the agency's opinion on 
individual applications has been valued and thus UNHCR could still 
play a positive role in having more sit-in people admitted to these 
programs.

+-------------------------------------------------------------------+
