So: U-hr
From: cispesnatl@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: carnet.alerts
Subject: action alert!!!!!
Date: 19 Jun 1996 15:32:27 -0800 (PST)

COMMITTEE IN SOLIDARITY WITH THE PEOPLE OF EL SALVADOR
National Office: P.O. Box 1801, New York, NY 10159 ~ 212-229-1290
3 Regional Offices: Boston, MA 617-524-1166 3 New York, NY
212-229-1290 3  Chicago, IL 312-227-2720 3  San Francisco, CA
415-648-6520 e-mail:cispesnatl@igc.apc.org; Fax 212-645-6657

C     I     S     P     E     S
ACTION ALERT

SALVADORAN GOVERNMENT AND MEDIA BLAME WORKERS FOR VIOLENCE WHILE
DEATH SQUADS ROAM FREE:
U.S. MUST PRESSURE TO BRING REAL CRIMINALS TO JUSTICE

June 19, 1996

On June 6, el Diario de Hoy, the right-wing daily paper, published
a story blaming public sector unions for plotting violent actions
to prevent privatization of ANTEL, the telecommunications company.
While labor has denied the charges, government officials including
the Vice Minister for Public Security have leveled veiled threats
of consequences against public workers.  Unionists fear that a
climate is being generated for death squad violence against
workers and particularly ASTTEL (the union of ANTEL workers) in
this time when they are rallying public opposition to a
privatization plan which will cut phone services, raise prices,
increase unemployment and further enrich a handful of wealthy
Salvadorans and international capital.

This scapegoating and vilifying of organized labor comes at a time
when ARENA is trying to divert attention from internal strife
which is widely considered linked to recent bombings.  On May 25,
a bomb blew up at SISA, an insurance company in which ex-President
Cristiani is the majority stockholder, only a month after a car
bomb exploded near Cristiani's home.

While Government officials and the right wing press blame workers
for escalating violence, the FMLN has used the attacks as an
example of the need go after the real criminals once and for all
by following up on the work of the Truth Commission and the Joint
Group to investigate and prosecute the death squads.

In late May, Salvador Snchez Cern, Coordinator of the FMLN,
released to a television station the names of death squad leaders
in Berlin, Usulutn who had recently met in that city.  The group
includes ex-military officers, purged from the army in the peace
process, as well as wealthy business people, landholders and the
current Head of Operations for the Land Bank.

While the Government and media hope to blame labor for violence
international solidarity must weigh in to defend the workers and
pressure the government to investigate the real criminals.

Suggested Action:

1. Get your Congressional Representative to fax the following
letter to John Hamilton, Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for
Latin America and the Caribbean and to send copies CC: to Anne
Patterson, Acting Assistant Secretary of State for Inter-American
Affairs and Ambassador James Dobbins, Special Assistant to the
President for Latin America at the National Security Council.

Sample letter******

John Hamilton Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for Latin
America and the Caribean Inter-American Affairs, State Department

    I am writing to express my grave concern with recent public
    declarations in El Salvador by the press and high-ranking
    officials against labor activists and the continued inaction
    on key components of the Peace Accords around public security
    and the death squads.


   A June 6th story in el Diario de Hoy and subsequent allegations
   by high-ranking officials in the Salvadoran Government,
   (including the Vice Minister of Public Security), charged
   public employees, as well as the FMLN, with plotting violence
   against the state to halt privatization of the
   telecommunications company ANTEL.  The PNC's Sub-Director for
   Operations, Rolando Garcia has stated publicly that the charges
   have not been confirmed.  But I question the motives of
   government officials who would so irresponsibly echo
   unconfirmed charges of this sort.

   In El Salvador's recent past, such accusations have given the
   green light to death squads and those death squads continue to
   act with impunity.  It has come to my attention that only a few
   weeks ago, in late May, the coordinator of the FMLN released a
   list of ex-military officers, landowners and the current head
   of Operations for the Land Bank who had allegedly met in the
   eastern part of El Salvador to discuss continued death squad
   activity.

   These events combined with the recent attacks against
   ex-President Cristiani make it more urgent than ever that
   legislative reforms to the police and the Penal Code, which
   remain stalled in the Legislative Assembly, and the pending
   reforms to Public Security reccomended by the UN Mission in El
   Salvador last fall, be implemented as soon as possible.

   Furthermore these events once again underline the need for a
   thorough investigation into violent acts in El Salvador and
   there would be nowhere more appropriate to set such a precedent
   than by following up on the Truth Commission and the Joint
   Group's recommendations to dismantle the death squad apparatus
   in that country.  The end of next month will mark two years
   since the Joint Group issued its report.

   This report contained an annex which was said to name names and
   detail evidence of death squad participants.  Yet to this date
   no progress can be measured regarding follow up to that
   information.

   I would like to know exactly what is the State Department doing
   to:
a) Express concern for unsubstantiated charges of violence being
made against unions;
b) Help overcome the deadlock in the legislature regarding the
police and penal reforms;
c) Pressure for implementation of the still pending
recommendations of the UN on Public         Security matters; and
d) Encourage a full investigation of the recent bombings and death
squad activity based on      the information contained in the
annex to the report of the Joint Group.

   I await your response regarding these matters.

Sincerely,

cc: Ann Patterson, Acting Assistant Secretary for Inter American
Affairs
      Ambassador James Dobbins, NSC
.
