<pre>
So: U-hr
From: ghrc@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: carnet.alerts
Subject: URGENT ACTION (FROM JENNIFER)
Date: 25 Jun 1996 12:03:19

From: "Alice Zachmann"  ghrc@igc.apc.org 



-------------- Enclosure number 1 ----------------
                            URGENT ACTION
   
   June 25, 1996
   
   Dear Friends,
   
     Well, I am finally back in the U.S. after a fairly hellish two month detour
   to Guatemala. I apologize once again to all those who organized events which
   I was unable to attend. I just repeat that my absence was not exactly
   voluntary.
   
     We did go to the Corte de Constitutionalidad over my marriage. Asisclo
   Valladares, my old pal, showed up in full force and made the following
   arguments against registering my marriage.
   
   1. I don't need to register my marriage to participate in the criminal case or
   exhumation...I could act as querellante adhesiva without it just like Rigoberta
   is in the Xaman case. I pointed out that I was cut out of the penal case since
   last year because my marriage is not registered...and so far cannot even file a
   motion as a result. The law allowing Rigoberta to act applies only to
   Guatemalan citizens.
   
   2. I am really trying to get money with the marriage...for example in my case
   against the CIA, I pointed out that I do not need to inscribe my marriage in
   Guatemala to proceed with my U.S. case...my Texas decree is quite enough.
   As for the OAS, they accepted my case without any such inscription way back
   in '93. After all, basic international law says that a marriage valid where
   celebrated is valid everywhere. That is also U.S. and Guatemalan law. Within
   Guatemala itself, I have long since allowed the statute of limitations to run. I
   can't sue for money there even if I wanted to. With this a lot of people started
   snickering in the back rows of the audience. Asisclo grew very red.
   
   3. Asisclo then said that I needed to get an order of execution to proceed...but
   this only applies to property judgements and is the equivalent of an order to
   garnish wages or levy on property etc. Guatemalan law itself says orders of
   marriage and divorce are registered instead of executed. That put an end to
   the other half of Asisclo's arguments.
   
   4. The really ugly part was that Asisclo once again hauled Everardo's elderly
   father and frightened sister into court. First he screamed to the judges that
   Everardo was a murderer and the marriage should not be inscribed. Then he
   said he cared so much about the father that he brought him here to make
   sure I could not steal his share of the inheritance. The father had his head in
   his lap most of the time and was shaking.
   
     I pointed out that so far no inheritance exists but that if any money
   damages do come through, the family will be the first to benefit, together with
   Guatemalan popular groups. I will not keep any money at all for myself that
   has its roots in Everardo's torture and murder.
   
     As for my relationship with the family, there are a number of things I
   cannot write about in this open letter, because it could put them in danger. All
   I can say is that we are in no way in an adverse position...and I presented my
   evidence to MINUGUA and asked them to look into the matter. Certain Church
   leaders are also aware of the situation.
   
   5. Asisclo also argued that since Everardo had no passport, he could never
   have entered Texas. This one made me smile a bit. Of course, no one has
   ever entered Texas without a passport.
   
     After the hearing a lot of visiting lawyers came up to congratulate us
   and tell us that Asisclo was left looking truly ridiculous. Asisclo of course, was
   in a rage and has launched a press onslaught against me that I have not seen
   since the good old days of the Jactancia case. Interestingly, no one on the
   street cares at all, and they come up to talk, shake hands, give me presents
   and urge me to keep on fighting. When a bus left me off in a bad
   neighborhood the other night, two families hurried out of their houses to walk
   me the five blocks home. They had recognized me from their windows! With
   that kind of treatment, who am I to give up?
   
     The real problem with all the press drive is that Asisclo is basically
   threatening the judges with political death if they rule the wrong way. Of
   course, in Guatemala, no one is free of politics and careers can indeed be
   destroyed if the upper class turns on them. This is my real concern. I therefore
   ask you to call the Guatemalan Embassy in Washington, DC ASAP (the ruling
   will come out any day) and urge that:
   
   1. The defamation campaign be ended. The ONLY thing the inscription of my
   marriage in Guatemala can change is my participation in the criminal case and
   the exhumation at Las Cabanas.
   
   2. The court be allowed to rule free of political pressure.
   
   3. The clear laws be upheld in this case and reciprocity be respected (i.e., that
   both countries have agreed to respect each other's marriages).
   
   4. Impunity be ended. Things are going badly in the Xaman case...several
   soldiers were just released after the judge tried desperately to resign for
   "personal" reasons. Helen Mack just had a number of her trial files destroyed.
   Obviously the army does not respect the courts.
   
     Thanks everyone. I am very glad to be home. I was beginning to get
   the creepy feeling that the press uproar was also a smokescreen...to make it
   seem as if I was so unpopular that patriotic feelings got out of control and I
   was murdered in an isolated incidence of common crime. I spoke with the
   Embassy about this...and pointed out the difference between what was said in
   the press and how I am treated in the streets. In any event, I am back safe
   and sound. Stay tune for the next installment. Abrazos, Jennifer.
   
   PLEASE CALL THE GUATEMALAN EMBASSY AS SOON AS POSSIBLE:  
   
   The Guatemala Embassy
   Ambassador Peter Lamport
   2220 R Street, NW
   Washington, DC 20008
   Tel. 202-745-4952  ext. 111
   Fax. 202-745-1908
.
