<pre>
So: U-hr
From: geo@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: dev.humansettl
Subject: Summer Inst. in Sustainable Living
Date: 31 May 1996 11:16:28 -0800 (PST)

Hello!  Here's some information on the 2nd annual Geocommons Summer
Institute on Sustainable Living and Eco-Village Design that will run from
June 30th to August 10th in southern New Hampshire.  It's a great program
with lots of hands-on learning.  There are still a few places open so if you or 
someone you know might be interested in attending, please contact us
a.s.a.p.  Thanks!!

Oh, and if you have access to the www, you can find more info about our 
organization and programs at <a href=http://www.ic.org/geo.>http://www.ic.org/geo.</a>

In community,
Daniel Greenberg

=========================================================================== 

                         GEOCOMMONS COLLEGE YEAR
     Summer Institute on Sustainable Living and Eco-Village Design

               University of New Hampshire Summer Session
                      June 30th - August 10th, 1996

In the summer beauty of New England hill country, 8-10 students and faculty 
will create a special learning community for sustainable living.  They will 
develop practical life skills,  ecological literacy,  cooperative community 
processes, and mindful awareness. 

A major goal will be to work on the design of an educational eco-village to 
be built in the near future on the Institute site at Derbyshire Farm.  This 
beautiful  75-acre  hilltop farm  in southern New Hampshire  is bordered by 
apple orchards and  2,000 acres  of protected wilderness.  Students will be 
introduced to a variety of ecological design systems such as  permaculture, 
biodynamic agriculture, passive solar construction, and Baubiologie (build- 
ing biology). Institute students will be guided by skilled faculty and will 
cooperatively guide each other in ways to apply their new learnings towards 
making their own campuses, communities, and homes more sustainable. 

Students will also have an  opportunity this year  to observe  the building 
and  organizational creation  of a miniature ecological village on the same 
farm.  This role-playing game for middle school students is called the Game 
of Village and will be run as a summer camp for five weeks during the Inst- 
itute.  "Homesteader" campers will construct model houses, schools, stores, 
and develop  systems of communication,  production, trade,  governance, and 
education.  

Summer Institute activities will include:

  - organic food production and healthy diets;
  - sense of place exploration;
  - bio-system study and site evaluation;
  - shelter & energy system design;
  - economic and career considerations;
  - nature and wilderness immersion;
  - community processes and consensus training;
  - development of shared values, visions, relationships, celebrations, and 
    mindfulness that form the "glue" for a sustainable learning community. 

COURSES AND CREDIT:  The 2 required courses are EC 687, Internship in Sust- 
ainable Living (4 cr.)  and EC 695, Special Topics in Environmental Conser- 
vation:  Eco-Village Design (3 cr.).  Both are credit-fail (ungraded).  The 
optional, graded course is  EC 595,  Problems in  Natural and Environmental 
Resources: The Human Experience in Nature (2 cr.). It will examine and com- 
pare the relationships to nature of Native American, Australian Aboriginal, 
and  Western scientist.  One major paper is required.  Non-UNH students are 
encouraged to attend this Institute. UNH credits can be easily transferred.

PARTICIPANTS:  The Summer Institute  is for applicants, ages 18 to 80, with 
some background in environmental studies and readiness for community living 
and self-development.  Flexibility, patience,  empathy,  a love for nature, 
and  high motivation  are key qualities.  Food is vegetarian.  Participants 
agree not to use alcohol, tobacco, drugs, TV,  or recorded music during the 
program in support of focused,  healthy group interaction and creative live 
arts & music making. There will be several celebrations.

SCHEDULE:  The daily schedule aims for a balance of physical, intellectual, 
emotional,  and spiritual elements as a conscious experiment in sustainable 
group living. The program embraces a 5 1/2-day weekly schedule and requires 
full participation in the training,  maintenance,  and process work of com- 
munity living.  Distinctions between work, play,  study, and  free time are 
put aside in a summer camp mood of trying out new lifeways. Sunday is a day 
for quiet, personal activities,  mindfulness practice, and hikes and excur- 
sions.  Wednesday afternoon and evening are unscheduled and free.

Cost:  $2,100 including room, board, and tuition.  ($300 extra for EC 595.) 
Some scholarships available.

For more information or application, contact: 

Gaia Education Outreach Institute 
Derbyshire Farm, Temple, NH  03084 
(603) 654-6705  geo@igc.org

=========================================================================== 

                     Geocommons Summer Institute, 1996
                         ACTIVITIES AND COURSEWORK

The following schedule describes the  typical daily rhythms  of the Geocom- 
mons Summer Institute.  We aim for a  balance of activities that engage the 
mind,  heart, and  body.  This schedule is  meant to be a template -- there 
will be some exceptions and changes.  For example,  outings and field trips 
will generally take  larger blocks of time.  Saturday morning  will be open 
until a  10 am council circle  which will allow a  deeper sharing of exper- 
iences and learnings.  Saturday evening will be a time for stories,  dance, 
and song, and Sunday will be a day for quiet, personal activities, mindful- 
ness practice, hikes, and excursions.  We may also occasionally shift week- 
day and weekend schedules.

            6:30:  Wake-up bell
    6:50 -  7:30:  Stretches, meditation, songs, poetry, silent walks
    7:30 -  8:15:  Breakfast and clean-up
    8:15 - 10:00:  Block I: check-in, announcements, seminar, presentations
   10:00 - 10:30:  Break, snack, stretches, long breaths and smiles
   10:30 - 12:00:  Block II: arts, nature, physical activities
   12:00 -  1:30:  Lunch, clean-up, siesta (cooking crew comes early)
    1:30 -  3:00:  Block III: creative applications and hands-on learning
    3:00 -  4:30:  Outdoor work, exercise, walks, etc.
    4:30 -  6:00:  Personal open time for study, writing, etc.
    6:00 -  7:30:  Dinner and clean-up (cooking crew comes early)
    7:30 -  9:00:  Block IV: study, group activities, and free time
    9:00 -  9:30:  Review of the day and closing

Students  will be expected  to keep  eco-village design journals,  share in 
group discussions, present on readings and research, carry out two or three 
individual projects,  write summary project papers, help with gardening and 
cooking,  and share in singing,  games, and  celebrations.  We will examine 
the following topics,  some more fully than others, depending on collective 
interests and talents:

ORIENTATION:  opening ceremony, tour of property, history of land, autobio- 
  graphies,  sense of place,  community agreements  and goals,  overview of 
  Derbyshire daily schedule, systems (food, laundry, recycling, etc.), eco- 
  village design overview, map-making, learning styles, intentions.

COMMUNITY:  models of community  (intentional communities,  cohousing, land 
  trusts, villages),  consensus decisions, conflict resolution,  democratic 
  governance, council circles, leadership.

FOOD:  vegetarianism and other diets, menu planning, cooking, wild edibles, 
  food preservation, tracing food sources, organic and biodynamic Community 
  Supported Agriculture, gardening, permaculture, marketing

BIO-SYSTEM:  flora and fauna, water, climate, soil types, carrying capacity 
  of the land, role of agriculture, forest management, bioregional context, 
  geological and biological histories, aesthetics.

BUILT-ENVIRONMENT:  architectural and ecological design arts, environmental 
  audit of existing structures,  site planning and geomancy, public/private 
  spaces,  renewable energy sources (solar, wind, biogas), non-toxic build- 
  ing materials (Baubiologie), wastewater treatment, zoning laws.

ECONOMICS:  ownership of land and buildings,  green businesses,  common vs. 
  private use of income and resources,  least-cost end-use analysis,  local 
  economies, sustainable livelihoods. 

NATURE IMMERSION:  artistic expression,  awareness exercises,  observation, 
  wilderness time.

"GLUE":  common values/ideologies,  celebrations, mindfulness,  sustainable 
  relationships.

=========================================================================== 

