So: U-hr
From: geo@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: dev.humansettl
Subject: North American Communities Semester
Date: 19 Jun 1996 17:29:50 -0800 (PST)

Hi.  I thought you might be interested in the following announcement about a 
new program called the North American Communities Semester that Geocommons 
College Year will be offering this Fall.  We also run an International 
Communities Semester in the Spring which takes students to communities in 
Europe (Plum Village and Findhorn) and India (Auroville and Mitraniketan) and 
a Summer Institute on Sustainable Living and Eco-village Design.  If you're 
interested in learning more about any of these programs, please ask me and/or 
check out our web site at <a href=http://www.ic.org/geo.>http://www.ic.org/geo.</a>  Thanks!

In community,
Daniel Greenberg

==============================================================================

                           Geocommons College Year
                  NORTH AMERICAN COMMUNITIES PILOT SEMESTER
                     September 4th - December 4th, 1996

A project of GEO Institute in cooperation with the University of New Hampshire


This experimental pilot program  will be an  intensive immersion into sustain- 
able community, ecology, and spirit. Three to six students and a faculty/guide 
will live and work in  inspiring communities and  develop awareness and skills 
for building a positive, sustainable future for humanity and the planet.

The program will begin in  southern New Hampshire on  September 4th  (after an 
optional Communities Conference at  Twin Oaks Community on Labor Day weekend). 
We will spend our first week  building our own  small community while learning 
about sustainability, mindfulness, and the communities we will visit.  Then we 
will embark on a  2 1/2 month journey  spending anywhere from  an afternoon to 
2 weeks in exemplary communities,  organizations, and places of natural beauty 
on the east coast of America.

Together, students and faculty will:

- Work side-by side with community members in kitchens, farms, businesses, and 
    service projects,
- Develop  skills in group dynamics,  consensus decision making, and  conflict 
    resolution,
- Explore sense of place and  nature awareness within both wild and human env-
    ironments,
- Learn  principles of  ecological design and  permaculture and  apply them to 
    specific communities, and
- Practice mindful,  sustainable living in a  daily balance of studies,  work, 
    recreation, & reflection.

Examples of the 10-20 communities we may visit include:  the Sirius Community, 
a spiritual, education center founded by former members of the Findhorn Found- 
ation in Scotland; Earthlands, an Earth-oriented, activist community; and Twin 
Oaks,  a feminist,  egalitarian community in  Virginia.  We are also exploring 
opportunities  to visit a Buddhist monastery, a Native American community, and 
an Amish or Hutterite colony. In early November, we will join a biennial meet- 
ing of the Fellowship for Intentional Communities at the Farm in Tennessee and 
then make our way back to New Hampshire for two concluding weeks of synthesis, 
portfolio completion, public presentations, local field trips,  next steps for 
college and career, and a closing celebration. 

FACULTY:  Daniel Greenberg will be this year's  primary faculty/guide  and has 
extensive experience in communal living and facilitating groups. He has worked 
& studied in over 20 communities,  including a year at the Findhorn Foundation 
and has co-led two student programs to international communities.  He received 
his PhD in Child Psychology studying children and education within U.S. inten- 
tional communities. In addition, we will draw upon dozens of skilled and know- 
ledgeable resource people within the communities we visit.

COURSEWORK & CREDIT:  Students will discuss common readings, keep journals and 
portfolios of their work, write several essays and papers, and engage in field 
study and service work.  Eight college credits are available for  two ungraded 
courses  through the  University of  New Hampshire:  Internship in Sustainable 
Living (4 cr.)  and  Sustainable Community Design (4 cr.).  UNH credits can be 
readily transferred to other schools.

TOTAL COSTS:  The approximate cost will be $4,300 for tuition, food, travel, & 
accomodations. Some scholarships are available.

    For more information or application, contact Daniel Greenberg at the:

                      Gaia Education Outreach Institute
                      Derbyshire Farm, Temple, NH  03084
                         (603) 654-6705; geo@igc.org
                            <a href=http://www.ic.org/geo>http://www.ic.org/geo</a>

.
