Subject: OMCT/TCD06225.1/FATWA/ON/WOMAN/REMO
Date: 29 May 1996 03:06:28

Subject: OMCT/TCD06225.1/FATWA/ON/WOMAN/REMOVED/CHAD

--=====================_833382696==_
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"



--=====================_833382696==_
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="iso-8859-1"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="TCD06115.ASC"

                        Women Appeal
                      Case TCD 061195.1
                Follow-up of Case TCD 061195
                             =20
The International Secretariat of OMCT/SOS-Torture has
just been informed of the removal of a death fatwa on Ms
Zahara Mahamat Yacoub, a Chadian journalist on whose
behalf we requested your intervention.

Brief reminder of the situation :
On 13 October 1995, two weeks after the showing of her
film "Dilemme au F=E9minin", the 15 mosques of the town of
Ndjamena cursed, excommunicated and condemned Ms Zahara
Mahamat Yacoub in their sermons by order of the High
Council of Islamic Affairs and the Imam of the grand
mosque of Ndjamena.  The film, which contained scenes of
nudity (through the showing of an excision) alongside
with an interview with the Chief Imam, was seen as an
offence against the Muslim religion.  Despite the gravity
of the situation, there was for a time no official action
taken to protect Ms Zahara Mahamat Yacoub.

New information :
According to information received from reliable sources,
Ms Zahara Mahamat Yacoub is now safe after extensive
lobbying from several international women's groups and
others caused Chadian President Idriss Deby to intervene
and put an end to harassment and the fatwa against her.

Observations :
The International Secretariat appreciates and wishes to
extend its deepest gratitude for the enormous response
from all the network members and other organisations and
individuals.


Geneva, 29 May 1996

