Date: 29 May 1996 20:59:20

From: Michael Marten  mam@tattoo.ed.ac.uk 

                   ****SCOTTISH CHURCHES' SUDAN GROUP***

*Please feel free to forward this to anyone you think might be interested!*
(You must include the following paragraph regarding copyright of material.)

[The information reproduced below consists primarily of news items which have
appeared in the printed Newsletter. Unless otherwise noted, you should assume
it is copyright Scottish Churches' Sudan Group. Therefore permission MUST be
requested if you wish to reproduce or distribute it in any form (permission
will normally be freely given provided full acknowledgments are included).
Items that are marked as being copyright for someone else may not be copied
without first contacting the copyright holder. Subscription details and our
address are located at the end of this document. If you have any comments or
would like to send us materials (possibly for inclusion in the Newsletter)
please write to us - all correspondance welcome!]
***************************************************************************
Issue No. 28                                                       MAY 1996
***************************************************************************

SANCTIONS 
In June of last year a group of Egyptian militant Islamists tried to
assassinate their country's leader as he arrived in Ethiopia to attend a
conference. Three suspects are believed to have fled to Sudan, and in January
the United Nations, at Ethiopia's request, gave Sudan 60 days to capture and
extradite the suspects. Last month the Sudanese regime - widely believed to
be sheltering or even directing the militant group - were told that they had
not complied with the UN demands.
The UN Security Council imposed sanctions on Khartoum at the end of April,
and they came into effect on 10/5/96. The sanctions are mild: they require
all UN member states to limit Sudan's diplomatic activity and forbid
international organisations from holding conferences in Sudan.
In March and April Sudanese politicians made desperate efforts to ward off
the more serious bans on arms sales and flights which were demanded by
Ethiopia, the Sudanese opposition and the USA. Sudan succesfully avoided
harsh penalties - Russia, China and Indonesia abstained in the vote, but the
resolution's mildness was really due to Egypt's change of heart on the
matter. Although her president was the target of the assassination attempt,
Egypt did not want to see sanctions imposed on yet another Arab country. Most
of all, Egypt is afraid that the Sudanese regime will lose the war in the
South. An independent South would complicate the issue of Nile waters, and
Egypt has a natural sympathy for the Arab rulers of Sudan in their struggle
to subdue the rebellious South.
The UN also demands that Sudan stop supporting international terrorism -
countries hostile to the Sudanese regime have long claimed that there are
training camps across Sudan where Islamist militants are trained in irregular
warfare. Osama bin Laden, a tall Saudi hero of the Afghan war who happens to
have a fortune of $300 million, is rumoured to pay for much of the training -
he now lives in Sudan. The cloak-and-dagger atmosphere of the whole affair
was heightened when someone claiming to be Mustafa Hamza, one of the
suspects, phoned an Arab newspaper in London from Afghanistan, to say that
none of the suspects were in Sudan, and that he and his friends didn't even
like the Sudanese government.
(Reuter 28/4/96, 7/5/96; ENA 28/4/96; Time 6/5/96)

HUMAN RIGHTS
The UN Human Rights Commission in Geneva issued a condemnation of Sudan's
human rights record in Geneva last month. Dr Gaspar Biro, the UN official
charged with investigating human rights abuses in Sudan, told the commission
that indisputable instances of torture, slavery and other abuses were still
being recorded. The Sudanese regime had banned Dr Biro from visiting Sudan
after his 1994 report, which made explicit reference to the inconsistency
between Sudan's Islamic law and Sudan's obligations under human rights
treaties which it has signed. This was taken as an affront to the faith, but
the regime is now trying to come to terms with Dr Biro again.
(Sudan News 11/4/96; Sudan Democratic Gazette 5/95)

FIGHTING IN THE EAST
The war in Sudan is spreading to the north. The Beja lands, which lie along
the Red Sea and the Eritrean border, in the east of Sudan, saw an armed clash
between the regime's forces and soldiers of the Beja Congress. The Beja are a
group of non-Arab Muslim tribes who have been alienated from the stridently
Arab culture and militant Islam propagated by the regime, which has allegedly
confiscated land from Beja farmers and given it to its own supporters.
Another armed group operating around the Eritrean border is the Sudan
Alliance Forces. They belong to the opposition National Democratic Alliance,
which groups together southern rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army and the
traditional Islamic oposition parties of the Arab north. Unlike the northern
establishment, the SAF is strongly secularist. But it enjoys the favour of
the SPLA and the Eritrean government.
A British journalist in Eritrea saw the SAF train with AK-47 rifles in
Eritrea, aiming at targets adorned with the photograph of Hassan al-Turabi,
the leader of Sudan's Islamists. The army, led by Brigadier Abdul Aziz
Khaled, claims to have killed 15 government troops at a garrison over the
border in April. Eritrea has promised to help organisations trying to
overthrow the militant Islamist regime.
The SPLA managed to get to the southern borders of the Arab north of Sudan in
March, but it has never managed to organise a war in the north. Its northern
allies might make a difference.
(Sudan Democratic Gazette 5/96; Guardian 11/5/96)

SADIQ REFUSES TO SPEAK
The Muslim feast of sacrifice [ 'id al-'adha] commemorates the sacrifice of
Ishmael, the Qur'an's version of the biblical story of the sacrifice of
Isaac. This year it fell at the end of April, and as usual al-Sadiq al-Mahdi,
Sudan's former prime minister and leader of the banned Umma party, led
worship at his family's Wad Nubawi mosque in Omdurman. The Mahdi family is
the most important in all Sudan, and in Sudan's complex religious politics,
has the allegiance of the Ansar, or followers of the Mahdi, a religious sect.
This time al-Sadiq refused to make a speech, calling on a relative, Abdel
Mahmoud Abo, to issue a denunciation of the government's handling of politics
and the economy, and its recent agreement with two small groups of Southern
rebels. He also attacked some of the novel interpretations of Islamic law
which the country's militant rulers employ to serve their interests.
Al-Sadiq, who has been derided in the past with the nickname Abu Kalam [the
father of talk], refused to speak, in fulfilment of a vow he made at the end
of Ramadan, no longer to call for a peaceful solution to the country's
current crisis. 
(al-Sharq al-Awsat 21/2/96; al-Hayat 21/2/96; Umma Party Information Office
UK 30/4/96)

WAR AND PEACE
Last month the Sudanese government signed a peace agreement with two
factional rivals of the rebel Sudan's People Liberation Army. The two groups,
led by Riek Machar and Kerubino Kuanyin, signed a Political Charter with
vague provisions for a referendum for the South, but with a firm commitment
to the unity of Sudan.
The charter was denounced as empty treachery by John Garang's SPLA, the main
rebel faction, and its Ugandan, Eritrean and Ethiopian allies. The SPLA
always maintained that their rivals were agents of Khartoum. The SPLA has
refused a number of peace overtures from Riek Machar over the past few months
- he split from Garang in 1991 accusing the latter of dictatorial vices.
Machar leads a loose alliance of commanders mainly from his own Nuer tribe.
His area has seen the success of grass-roots peace initiatives, perhaps made
possible by his more open approach to government. One of his commanders,
William Nyoun, rejoined Garang last year, but was recently assassinated by
another Machar commander.
Kuanyin has long been regarded as a brutal agent of Khartoum, but some
observers sympathise with Machar, who had to choose between surrender to
Garang, who refused all offers of reconciliation - and between this agreement
with a discredited and desperae government. By choosing to ally himself with
Khartoum, Machar and his mainly Nuer supporters do not have to submit to
Garang's authoritarianism. The Nuer and other tribes in Upper Nile can hope
for greater independence of actions as clients of Khartoum than they can as
subordinates of Garang.
It is hard to interpret the agreement's significance - it may allow the
tribes of Upper Nile, geographically and historically closer to the north and
to Ethiopia, space and time to get on with life in the midst of a long
running conflict; it may help the government at a time when it faces military
and diplomatic catastrophe; it may weaken the increasingly powerful SPLA war
machine, backed by the US and African countries. But it will certainly place
almost intolerable pressure on the church, the only group that brings
together Southerners from all tribes. Machar's tribe is mostly Presbyterian,
while Garang's supporters tend to belong to Evangelical, Catholic and
Anglican churches. Through five years of inter-factional fighting in the
South, the churches have made a united stand against cruelty and tribal
hatreds. This stand will now be tested again. See PRAYER
(Report on the situation available on request from 73124.376@compuserve.com -
please quote your name and request "Sudan Analysis")

***************************************************************************

PRAYER
Bishop Paride Taban, the leader of the Roman Catholic Church in Southern
Sudan, recently appealed to all Christians to rise above tribal identities
and work together to build a nation where love and justice would prevail
everywhere:
In [the epistle to] the Hebrews, it is said God sent people to keep the words
of God, but nobody listened and they suffered a lot.  And Jesus Christ came
also to tell them the same message, yet nobody took him seriously. In Sudan
there are prophets prophesising to their people: you reconcile, you forgive,
you be a nation, you be the sons and daughters of one family, but nobody
listens, he said. The Bishop pointed out that since 1991 the church had been
prophesising to the people of Southern Sudan on the need for togetherness,
telling them that if they would not reconcile among themselves they could
lose more lives, but this went on deaf ears.
(NSCC News 2/96)
Please pray for the churches and Christians in South Sudan who must confront
the fats of violence between rival Southerners; pray that they might be able
to hear God calling them to peace and reconciliation.

***************************************************************************

WHAT PEACE FOR THE NUBA?
This was the title of a London conference last month. Ian Mackie, one of our
members, was a speaker and he sent us this report on the proceedings:
The conference proved to be an effective occasion in which a range of issues
concerning the Nuba people were highlighted to a gathering of about 100
people. The aim was of course to project the situation to a wide audience, by
means of the range of people who attended. The Foreign Office, at least two
embassies and a number of organisations concerned with the state of Sudan
were represented, <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a> it may be presumed that the aim was achieved.
The day's programme began with a number of contributions on the politics and
history of the situation and went on to cover the war's impact on religion,
women's and human rights. Media coverage of this terrible and inaccessible
conflict was also discussed.
My own contribution dealt with what I consider to be the basic issues which
will affect the Nuba once a change comes to the Sudan: namely restoring their
rights to their traditional lands in a way that will clearly define their
future. The existing government sponsored agricultural developments gather
small family farms into large plantations which are sold to the government's
supporters. The indigenous inhabitants are driven off their lands, and return
to them only as cheap or slave labour. This must be replaced by systematic
allocation of land to individual free-hold farmers, and the providing of the
basic infra-structures to make this possible. I stated that this could be
achieved at not too great cost, and once done, it would contribute to the
prosperity of the Sudan, as well as that of the Nuba.
In the present very difficult situation the above would seem to be only
wishful thinking, but not <a name=L10002></a><a href=#L10003>so</a>! Throughout the day I was able to detect some
spirit of optimism because the present government's position was shown to be
tenuous, and bowed beneath the burden of its own cruelty and injustice.
Change will of course come - and among the possibilities raised was that of a
federal Sudan, in which a Nuba State could make a contribution to overall
national government.
I was most impressed by young people present who, at personal risk, had not
long since returned from the Nuba Mountains and who could speak of the
unbroken spirit of the Nuba whom they met. It can be taken as certain that
all the attempts at genocide and obliteration of the Nuba name have failed,
and the tolerant Nuba - Christian, Muslim or Animist - will rebuild their
communities and their culture; and shall be an example to others!
Prayer is never misplaced nor does it ever fail: the need for continuing
prayer for the Nuba was never more plain.

OTHER NEWS
Economic news: President al-Bashir has promised that his country will start
the commercial production of oil. Speaking in Saudi Arabia, where he was
attending celebrations to mark the end of the hajj, or pilgrimage to Mecca,
he said that Sudan will produce 10,000 barrels a day starting in June. (Suna
4/5/96)
Plane crash: Five planes have crashed in Sudan this year, <a name=L10003></a><a href=#L10004>so</a> many that the
country's new parliament held a debate on the problem. Bad weather and
difficulties in maintaining planes in such a poor country have contributed to
the problem, but the minister of aviation says he is not responsible. The
latest crash happened n a sandstorm near Haj Youssef, part of the Sudanese
capital. 53 people died, including 26 students from a university in South
Sudan. The plane was flying from Wau, in Bahr al-Ghazal, to Khartoum. (AP
4/5/96; Reuter 6/5/96; Suna 7/5/96)

HUMAN RIGHTS CAMPAIGN
The Sudanese Victims Of Torture Group has expressed its grave concern for the
safety of 36 people illegally detained at Kober Prison. The regime's security
services have allegedly set up a secret torture centre or "ghost house" in
this old Khartoum prison. It is believed that a great number of these
illegally detained people are suffering from various problems, such as skin
problems, joint problems or breathing problems (asthma). They include one
child, Mohmed Hussain Ali, a 14 year old student.
Please write to the Sudanese authorities urging them to:
- take the appropriate measures to guarantee the safety of Mohmed Hussain Ali
and his 35 adult companions and order their immediate release if they are
being detained without valid charges or, if such charges exist, bring them to
a fair trial.
- guarantee a full, impartial enquiry into the facts, concerning the supposed
illegal detention of all the persons above mentioned, identify those
responsible, bring them to trial, and punish them according to the law
- ensure in all circumstances respect for human rights and fundamental
freedoms in accordance with national laws and international standards
Address: His Excellency Lieutenant General Omar Hassan al-Bashir, President
of the Republic, People's Palace, PO Box 281, Khartoum, Sudan.
(OMCT/SOS-Torture, Geneva, 6 May 1996)
 
THE WAR DRAGS ON, BUT SUDANESE CHRISTIANS REFUSE TO GIVE UP HOPE
by Alexa Smith
NAIROBI, Kenya--Despite more than 29 years of civil war, with no end in
sight, most Sudanese Christians say they have hope that someday the violence,
homelessness and political instability will end. That hope is not <a name=L10004></a><a href=#L10005>so</a> much
eschatological or political as it is prophetic, for the resurrection hope <a name=L10005></a><a href=#L10006>so</a>
typical among Sudanese is tempered by a punitive edge.
Many Sudanese understand the words of the eighth-century BC prophet in Isaiah
18 to be a prediction of Sudan's current torment - and the coming redemption
of its "tall and smooth" people who are "feared near and far." Those words
bring both comfort and conflict to thse who are trying to make sense of the
persistence of evil, because the same God the Bible depicts as suffering with
the people is also understood here to be testing the helpless faithful -- and
punishing the faithless -- in the midst of the seemingly endless war.
"Everything has failed. Everything you can think of humanly has failed," said
the Rev. Haruun Ruun, executive director of the New Sudan Council of Churches
in Nairobi, about the violence that persists in Sudan between tribes and
between armies. "The only hope people have is in God who created them ... in
the Holy Spirit who gives strength and courage to stand up and endure the
situation - not just now, but tomorrow and next year. "There seems no end to
it." The New Sudan Council of Churches consists of Protestant, Catholic and
Pentecostal churches in the areas of southern Sudan controlled by the
Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA), which is fighting the
fundamentalist Islamic government in Khartoum for self-determination for the
largely black Christian and animist people of the south.
To date, more than 1.5 million Sudanese have been killed and at least 5
million more are refugees, who pour into makeshift camps outside Khartoum
that are routinely bulldozed back down into the dry Sahara that surrounds the
capital of the once-united country. In the south, people hide in moveable
villages deep in the bush. They hide not only from government troops, but
from one or both of the rebel armies that are fighting each other to control
southern Sudan's people and its much coveted natural resources, including
vast supplies of timber and oil. "This is not a new thing ... <a name=L10006></a><a href=#L10007>so</a> we will
endure it," argued a minister in Khartoum, who said the biblical narratives
tell of a God who allows suffering and somehow redeems it - from the
wandering of Hebrew ex-slaves in the wilderness to the nailing of Jesus to
the cross at Golgatha. But he refuses to raise questions about why the
warfare persists because, he said, there is also resurrection, and that means
no problem is hopeless. "Why should the people of Israel suffer for 40 years?
Why only Israel at the time? Why not other nations? When a problem comes to
you, you wonder, Why me and not others?'" And yet he insists that God allows
evil to happen, and even if a biblical prophecy predicts unavoidable
disaster, there is still hope for a yet unseen future.
Trying to make sense of the sheer persistence of evil is nothing new to
Africans who have, for centuries, had to wonder why there is <a name=L10007></a><a href=#L10008>so</a> much
suffering, according to Dr. Setri Nyomi of Nairobi's All Africa Conference of
Churches. Both traditional African religions and some strains of Christianity
have left behind legacies of divine punishment that often re-emerge when
theodicy is broached.
Nyomi told the Presbyterian News Service that most of Africa would say God
allows - but does not cause - evil. "The question is more What are we called
upon to do?' than Why is this happening to us?' Whether or not God allows
evil to happen is secondary," he said. But whether God actually inflicts
hardship as some sort of punishment or simply allows the consequences of
human sin to hold sway, even over the innocent, is where the debate gets
murkier. And it does prompt questions among those who continue suffering year
after year.
"Will God only punish the poor people but not the rich people in Sudan? Will
God only punish the black race but not the brown race in Sudan? It is a
conflict in our minds," said one southern Sudanese pastor, stressing that
most of the war has been fought in the south, displacing people and
destroying twns and fields. "We may not be the first people to ask this: If
God is just, why is this happening?' This question is in the minds of my
people. ...
"But," he said, drawing on scriptural stories, "to find blessing from God
involves some suffering and pain. ... Although God is just and everything
comes from him, there are also times when God wants to test us." But it is a
short step from a God who tests the faithful to one who punishes the
faithless -- particularly when the source of the quandary is a prophet's cry
of impending doom for people who have forgotten the God who delivered them
from Egypt. While some Sudanese attest that humans do evil and cause horrible
suffering, others understand God to be the source of all things.
"We accept this [war] on us as maybe from our sin - this is punishment being
done to us ...," one theological student told the Presbyterian News Service.
"We also have to examine why this punishment is given through the hands of
other people. Sudanese really know what Isaiah preached ... the Sudan."
The Rev. Paul Bol, executive secretary of the Presbyterian Church of Sudan
(in southern Sudan), said the Bible is clear about how the sins of the father
bring punishment to the children. "Adam and Eve," he said, "disobeyed and sin
fell to everybody in this world simply because they are Adam and Eve's
ancestors."
The tension between God's mercy and wrath is one the prophets well
understood. But most Sudanese preachers preach love: how to live together
though the world seems to be crumbling, how to trust that the church in other
parts of the world has not forgotten them, how to believe that the vision of
God is more powerful than the great struggle that has swallowed Sudan,
Africa's largest country.
"There are times when our faith is brought into question," Ruun told the
Presbyterian News Service. But he points out that despite Sudan's horrific
problems, the church -- virtually the only stable institution left in
southern Sudanese society -- is growing enormously. "There are times when you
see the grace coming in ... and you begin to see light in spite of the
difficulties. Somehow you see that grace ... and it gives hope. ...
Ruun explained that worship in Sudan is jammed because people have watched
human solutions fail over and over. "They don't see any other solution," he
said. "But they see hope and solution in God."
(PCUSA NEWS 18/4/96)

