Subject: Sudan News & Views - 19
Date: 03 Jun 1996 22:12:44

From: yasin@dircon.co.uk (Yasin Miheisi)

--=====================_833772835==_
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"



--=====================_833772835==_
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="iso-8859-1"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="SNV19.TXT"

=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D

              S U D A N : N E W S &  V I E W S =20
                  =20
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D
  Issue No 19                                June 1995            =20
_________________________________________________________________
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
+ 'Sudan News & Views' is an independent electronic Newsletter  +
+  working to advocate peace, human rights and humanitarian aid +
+  for the Sudan.                                               +
+                                                               +
+                  * Editor: Dr. Yasin Miheisi *                +
+                                                               +
+ * Distribution is free of charge.                             +=20
+ * Reposting and reproduction are allowed (with acknowledgement). =20
+ * Comments and Subscription Requests To: yasin@dircon.co.uk   +
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In this issue:=20

* EDITOR'S NOTE
* WILL THE NIF COME OF ITS SENSES?  By Guest Writer: Dr. Lam Akol
* SUDAN SANCTIONS
* SUDAN ELECTIONS
* FIGHTING IN THE SOUTH
* PEACE DEAL OR MILITARY PACT?
* SUDAN PLANE CRASHES
* SUDAN HUMAN RIGHTS
* ECONOMIC POINTERS
* SHORT NEWS ITEMS
-----------------------------------------------
=20
* EDITOR'S NOTE

  Starting from this issue, we are introducing a new feature in the=20
newsletter. Guest writers are invited to contribute an article of their=20
views and analysis of the current situation in Sudan. We are pleased=20
to start this feature by an article written to 'Sudan News & Views'=20
by Dr. Lam Akol Ajawin, Leader and C-in-C of the SPLA-United.=20
Dr. Lam was a lecturer in the Faculty of Engineering - University of=20
Khartoum, before he joined the SPLA. Dr. Lam and Riek Machar headed=20
the split from the SPLA mainstream, led by John Garang, in 1991.=20
Later Lam and Riek fell out and Riek became leader of the Southern=20
Sudan Independence Movement and Army (SSIM/A). Recently Riek Machar=20
signed a peace deal with Khartoum.
  Please note that articles by guest writers express the writer's views=20
which do not necessarily coincide with the editor's.
  =20

* WILL THE NIF COME OF ITS SENSES? =20
  By Dr. Lam Akol

 The NIF fundamentalist dictatorship in Khartoum is running out of=20
tricks. It has pulled several out of the hat but to no avail.
In February/March, in an attempt to legitimize the dictatorship,=20
the NIF organized an election for the Presidency and a Parliament.=20
The elections results were known before the voting took place.=20
When the votes were counted, there were no surprises at all.=20
The fact, however, remained that the voters failed to turn up and,=20
according to independent observers, the voter participation was less=20
than 20%. The whole undertaking turned out to be an expensive exercise=20
in futility. Yet, the regime boasted of a free and fair election,=20
high voter turnout and of having got a mandate from the Sudanese=20
people !! Everybody in Sudan knew that the whole affair was a sham=20
and people wonder who the regime was trying to fool.
  Following immediately after the 'election', the media controlled by=20
the regime were full of statements that it was carrying out extensive=20
contacts with the various political forces inside the country with a=20
view of forming a broad-based government. After several weeks of such=20
contacts, the ministerial line-up was announced. Far from being=20
broad-based, the new cabinet was characterized by the inclusion=20
of NIF zealots in key portfolios in bigger numbers than before.=20
There was no doubt the NIF had decided to monopolize power in an=20
open way. All the masks were dropped.
  Then in April, the NIF pulled out what it believed was its greatest=20
propaganda coup. This was the <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a>-called charter signed with SIMM/A=20
leaders in Khartoum. The government propaganda machine presented it=20
as the acme of success of their 'Peace from Within' policy, and that=20
peace was at long last at hand. Not long after the propaganda=20
hullabaloo, the reality dawned on the NIF leaders that the trick=20
could not hoodwink the people - least of all the southerners.=20
People recognized it for what it was: a propaganda stunt to portray=20
the NIF regime as a peace maker at the time when the UN Security=20
Council was about to debate the measures to be taken against it=20
for promotion of state terrorism. The signatories to the charter=20
had surrendered to the regime well before the charter was made public.=20
The only significant thing about the agreement was the military=20
alliance between the NIF and Riek Machar to fight the two SPLA=20
factions. This can hardly be a 'success' to the regime. For all=20
this time the NIF have not been short of manpower to fuel its war=20
endeavour. It has the regular army, the Popular Defence Force and=20
the southern militias (the <a name=L10002></a><a href=#L10003>so</a>-called friendly forces). These=20
military and paramilitary units and formations were ruthlessly=20
used to persecute a dirty war against the southern Sudanese.=20
There is nothing new or special the joining of Riek will add beyond=20
the above role. Southerners were loud and clear in their rejection=20
of the deal. They would have nothing to do with it.
  Realizing failure to attract support to the 'charter', the NIF=20
regime resorted to cheap disinformation. The latest in this direction=20
was the claim by the regime that the Deputy Chairman of the=20
SPLM-United had signed the charter on behalf of the Movement.=20
The man they were talking about, James Othow Along, was and still=20
is an NIF government Commissioner of Toga province since=20
November 1995!!. There is no way he could have been a member of the=20
SPLM-United, which is fighting the regime, let alone being a Deputy=20
Chairman. In desperation, the regime did not care to consider the=20
implications of such a blatant lie. This can only be done by the=20
NIF since one of their favourite principles is that: 'a lie in the=20
advance of God's cause is permissible'. The jihad the NIF is=20
undertaking in the south, no doubt, passes as God's cause!.
  While the NIF continues to hide its head in the sand, the world is=20
not blind to its theatrics nor will realities be different from what=20
they are. The war continues to rage in the south, the economy=20
continues to decline and life continues to get more difficult for=20
the common man both in the north and south. These issues will have=20
to be confronted headlong if the regime hopes to survive.
  Peace is the most central issue in the resolution of the problems=20
facing the regime. The NIF knows quite well that the only realistic=20
way to arrive at a meaningful peaceful settlement is for the regime=20
to return to the negotiating table it left in September 1994. That=20
is the IGAD-mediated peace talks between the GOS on the one side=20
and the SPLM-United and SPLM-Torit on the other. It is time the NIF=20
zealots abandoned tricks and come down to earth and face the stark=20
realities of the war-ravaged Sudan. Otherwise, they will find=20
themselves swimming against a very strong current.

=20
* SUDAN SANCTIONS =20
=20
  The UN Security Council had voted on April 26 to impose diplomatic=20
and travel sanctions on Sudan, to take effect on May 10. The=20
resolution 1054, which warns of additional possible sanctions=20
if Sudan did not surrender three Egyptians wanted for trying=20
to assassinate President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa last year,=20
was approved by a vote of 13 for and none against, with abstentions=20
by Russia and China.=20
  The failure of the council to implement tougher sanctions, sought=20
by the US, Ethiopia and other western countries, was mainly due to=20
the campaign led by Egypt against imposing economic and military=20
sanctions, on the pretext that they would hurt ordinary Sudanese=20
people, and the reservations of Russia and China, who have their=20
own political and economic interests. Both have signed deals for=20
oil exploration in Sudan.
  Although being the main victim of Sudan's activities, Egypt=20
objected to an arms embargo for fear it would benefit southern rebels,=20
lead to southern secession and complicate its interests in the Nile=20
waters.
  The US was the first country to implement the UN resolution.=20
On May 14, the US ordered the information attach=E9, El-Sadig Bakhiet,=20
to leave the country, thus reducing the Sudanese diplomats in Washington=20
to five. The movement of the remaining embassy staff and Sudan's=20
UN mission was restricted to a 25-mile radius of Washington or=20
New York. The US had, last month, expelled the second secretary of=20
the Sudanese mission to the UN, Ahmed Yousif Mohamed, for his=20
connections with the terrorist group convicted for plotting to=20
blow up the UN building in New York.=20
  Britain followed suit by expelling 3 Sudanese diplomats and=20
restricting the movement of other embassy staff. This was followed=20
by other countries; France, Germany and Canada had each ordered the=20
expulsion of one diplomat from its Sudanese embassy. Egypt had=20
asked Sudan to reduce its diplomatic staff in Cairo from 45 to 7.  =20
  Some countries indicated they will ignore the resolution.=20
Hassan al-Turabi, parliament speaker and leader of the NIF,=20
attended a meeting of Arab parliament members in Syria,=20
Vice-President Zubair Mohamed Salih returned from an official=20
visit to Iran last week and State Minister for Foreign Affairs,=20
Ghazi Salah el-Din, visited Holland, despite the UN resolution's call=20
to restrict the entry of Sudanese officials. Several other officials=20
are scheduled to visit Turkey, Algeria and Iran.
  Under pressure and fearing additional measures from the SC at the=20
end of the 60-day ultimatum, Sudan embarked on a campaign to win=20
support and to improve its strained relations with both Egypt and=20
the US. There are reports that talk of a secret deal between Sudan=20
and Egypt, reached after a secret visit by an Egyptian official=20
to Khartoum and a meeting between the foreign ministers of the=20
two countries in Cairo. Khartoum reportedly agreed to get rid of=20
all Egyptian Islamic groups in Sudan in exchange for better=20
relations with Egypt.=20
  Sudan, in the past few weeks, sent mixed signals. President=20
Al-Bashir was quoted as saying his government was expelling all=20
opposition groups. A few days later, a statement issued by the=20
Presidency denied the remarks and said that Sudan had not asked=20
any Arab national to leave and that anything published was baseless.=20
At the same time, the Palestinian Islamist group Hamas, which has an=20
office and bases in Sudan, said they had no intention of leaving=20
Sudan and that their office in Khartoum will continue with its=20
activities as normal.
  The implicit acknowledgment that militants had indeed received=20
refuge in Sudan, was further confirmed by the Foreign Minister,=20
Ali Osman Taha, who said in an interview published last week, that=20
they had asked Arabs suspected of terrorism to leave Sudan. He also=20
revealed that the Saudi businessman, Osama Bin Ladin, who is=20
believed to be the financier of many radical Islamic groups,=20
had voluntarily left Sudan to Afghanistan to 'put an end to=20
pretexts'. However, some reports alleged that yet another deal was=20
struck with Saudi Arabia to deport Bin Ladin in exchange for oil.
  Sudan had also made overtures to the US and Israel, in a desperate=20
attempt at breaking its strong international isolation. President=20
Al-Bashir, and other Sudanese officials, had repeated calls=20
for 'the continuation of dialogue between Sudan and the USA, with=20
the view to resolving issues of difference between the two=20
countries'. Recent news had reported that the ex-Vice President,=20
Joseph Lagu, had presented the Sudanese authorities with an=20
American proposal for improving relations. Lagu had returned=20
to Washington with Sudan's answer to the proposal, the contents=20
of which are not yet known.=20
  Contact with Israel was reportedly made by Salah el-Din Karrar,=20
Minister for Cabinet Affairs, in a visit last month to Morocco=20
and Qatar, where he made contacts with Israel officials, in view=20
of establishing a non-official relation.

=20
* SUDAN ELECTIONS =20

  As widely expected, Omer Al-Bashir won by a 75% vote in the election=20
for the Presidency, which took place from 6 to 17 March, in which=20
he faced 40 little-known candidates. The presidential elections=20
were held simultaneously with parliamentary elections.
  Last January, 125 people were appointed to the 400-member=20
parliament. Fifty parliamentary candidates, including most of=20
the government ministers, won uncontested (termed by the government=20
media as 'silent consensus'), and eleven southern constituents did=20
not vote because of the civil war, making the number of seats=20
contested as 214.
  An overwhelming majority of parliamentary seats were swept by=20
supporters of the National Islamic Front (NIF). Hassan al-Turabi,=20
leader of the NIF, was elected, unopposed, as speaker for parliament,=20
thus putting him back in public office after more than six years as=20
an ideologue active behind the scenes.
  All the major political parties and opposition forces boycotted=20
the elections. According to the Election Commission, about 5.5 million=20
out of the 10 million eligible voters participated in the election.=20
However, opposition sources estimated a much lower figure.=20
The opposition NDA dismissed the elections as a 'desperate attempt=20
to legitimize an isolated dictatorship rejected by the Sudanese=20
people and the international community'.
  After much waiting and speculation, the new cabinet was announced=20
last month, reflecting very few changes. The key positions of=20
foreign affairs, defence and interior remained unchanged. The=20
Minister of Economics, Abdalla Hassan Ahmed, however, was sacked=20
and given the position of Governor of the Bank of Sudan.=20
The following are the members of the new cabinet:
-  Brigadier Abdel Rahim Mohamed Hussain, Minister at the Presidency.=20
-  Brigadier (retired), Salah el-Din Karrar, Minister for Cabinet Affairs.=
=20
-  Lieutenant General Hassan Abdel Rahman Ali, Minister of Defence.=20
-  Ali Osman Mohamed Taha, Minister of Foreign Affairs.=20
-  Brigadier Bakri Hassan Salih, Minister of Interior=20
-  Abdel Basit Sabdarat, Minister of Justice.=20
-  Brigadier Eltayeb Ibrahim Mohamed Khair, Minister for Culture and=20
   Information.=20
-  Dr Ali Al Haj Mohamed, Minister of Federal Affairs=20
-  Dr Abdel Wahab Osman, Minister of Finance and National Economy=20
-  Osman Al Hadi Ibrahim, Minister of External Trade=20
-  Badr el-Din Suleiman, Minister of National Industry=20
-  Dr Nafei Ali Nafei, Minister of Agriculture and Forests=20
-  Moussa Mak Kour, Minister of Animal Wealth=20
-  Dr Yagoub Moussa Abu Shoura, Minister of Irrigation=20
-  Dr Awad Ahmed Aljaz, Minister of Energy and Mining=20
-  Major General (retired) Albino Akol Akol, Minister  of Transport=20
-  Major General (retired) Al Hadi Bushra, Minister of Roads and=20
   Communications.=20
-  Colonel Galwak Deng Garang, Minister of Survey and Construction=20
   Development=20
-  Major General (retired) Tigani Adam Al-Tahir, Minister of=20
   Aviation=20
-  Mohamed Tahir Aila, Minister  of Environment and Tourism=20
-  Dr Abdel Whahab Abdel Rahim Bob, Minister of Higher Education and=20
   Scientific Research=20
-  Dr Kabashour Kuku, Minister of General Education=20
-  Mohamed Osman Khalifa, Minister of Social Planning=20
-  Angelo Beda, Minister for Public Service=20
-  Ms Ihssan Abdalla Ghabshawi, Minister of Health=20
-  Mohamed Al Amin Khalifa, Secretary General of the High Council=20
   for Peace=20
-  Abu el-Gasim Mohamed Ibrahim, Minister for Relations at the=20
   Parliament=20
   State (junior) Ministers:=20
   Foreign Ministry: Father Gabriel Rurec, Dr Mustafa Osman Ismail=20
   Ministry of Finance and National Economy: Dr Izz el-Din Ibrahim,=20
   Dr Sabir Mohamed Hassan=20
   Ministry of Federal Affairs: Dr Ibrahim Abu Aouf, Brigadier Abdalla=20
   Safi El-Nour, John Dor=20
   Ministry of Social Planning: Brigadier Yousif Abdel Fatah Mahmoud,=20
   Dr Majzoub Al-Khalifa, Dr (Mrs) Sayda Mohamed Bushara=20
   Ministry of Transport: Omar Salman=20
   Ministry of Roads and Communications: Major General Sayed Elhusseini=20
   Abdel Karim=20
   Ministry of Public Service: Abdel Rahman Nur El-Din, Dr Adam=20
   Mohamed Baluoh=20
   Advisors to the President of the Republic: Brigadier Bakri=20
   Hassan Salih, Advisor for Security Matters; Major Ibrahim=20
   Shams el-Din, Advisor for Defence; Ahmed Ibrahim El-Tahir,=20
   Legal Advisor with the Status of Federal Minister.=20


* FIGHTING IN THE SOUTH =20

  The SPLA mounted a new offensive along the Ethiopian border,=20
thus shifting its combat activities northwards. Since March, the=20
SPLA launched a major offensive against government forces in the=20
northeastern part of southern Sudan and southern Blue Nile province.
  In mid-March, the SPLA announced it had captured the garrison=20
town of Khor Yabus in the Blue Nile province. The same week, the=20
SPLA forces overran the army garrison in Pachalla in Upper Nile=20
province. The SPLA said, in a surprise attack,  1,500 government=20
troops stationed in Pachalla were killed, wounded or dispersed.=20
The SPLA also said its troops ambushed a Sudanese army brigade=20
between Chali and Khor Yabus, which was apparently attempting to=20
recapture Ohor Yabus. 'In a fierce battle that lasted 40 minutes,=20
the army brigade of about 1,500 men was completely annihilated',=20
the SPLA statement said.
  On April 10, the SPLA captured the settlements of Tami, Shima=20
and Uza in areas bordering Ethiopia, after heavy artillery shelling.
  The Sudanese authorities confirmed the take over of the army=20
garrisons and accused Ethiopia of  carrying out the attacks.=20
Ethiopia denied any involvement and accused Sudan of deploying=20
troops near the border and killing peasants in cross-border raids=20
in preparation for war.
  Last month, Sudan claimed Ethiopian troops killed 860 people=20
during cross-border bombardments in support of the SPLA.
  On May 12, the SPLA said it ambushed an army convey proceeding=20
from Waw to Warab in southern Sudan, where seven government troops=20
were killed.
  On another development to the armed struggle in Sudan, The Sudanese=20
Allied Forces (SAF), headed by Brigadier Abdel Aziz Khalid and=20
includes former army officers and soldiers, mounted two successful=20
attacks on military camps near the northeastern town of Kassala.=20
SAF say they killed 15 government militiamen on a dawn raid on=20
April 20, and 6 soldiers in a raid on May 19. The group said=20
they had seized rockets and radios from the government bases near=20
the Eritrean border.

There were also recent reports of mutiny by some army units in the=20
south. One report claimed that 3 battalions of the 3rd brigade,=20
currently deployed between Juba and Torit, refused to obey orders=20
and held two senior officers for some time before releasing them.=20
The soldiers fired in the air to express their protest at=20
a number of issues. The soldiers had not been paid salaries=20
for the last three months, their term of duty in the south=20
had expired three years ago, and some officers objected to the=20
way the war is being conducted. A senior military official from=20
the General Command in Khartoum was sent to meet with the soldiers=20
and discuss their demands.


* PEACE DEAL OR MILITARY PACT? =20

  Riek Machar, leader of the Southern Sudan Independence Movement=20
(SSIM), had signed a peace charter in Khartoum with the government=20
of Sudan on April 10. The agreement was signed by first=20
Vice-President Zubair Mohammad Salih for the government,=20
Riek Machar for SSIM and Karbino Kwanyin Bol for the SPLA-
Bahr al-Ghazal faction.
  Bol was a founding member of the SPLA in 1983 and was Garang's=20
deputy until 1987, when he was arrested and imprisoned by Garang. He=20
was released in 1991 and soon after joined SPLA-United, which had=20
split from Garang's mainstream SPLA in 1991.
  The ceremony was held in the grounds of the republic palace, and=20
attended by President al-Bashir, Hassan al-Turabi and several=20
ministers and officials.
  The agreement calls for the resolution of the conflict through=20
peaceful and political means, re-affirms the unity of  Sudan with=20
its known boundaries which should be preserved. 'Its entity shall=20
be secured against all internal and external dangers. The two=20
parties shall endeavour to keep peace, justice and supremacy of=20
values of right, good and virtue,' the charter said. It stated=20
that after peace and stability and a reasonable level of=20
development had been established in the south, then at the end of=20
an unspecified interim period a referendum should be held to=20
enable the people there to determine their political aspirations.=20
Under the charter, shari'a (Islamic law) and custom are given as=20
the source of legislation.
  The agreement was criticized by many as a worthless piece of=20
paper since the SPLA, led by John Garang, the main actor in the=20
conflict, was not party to it. Garang accused Machar of=20
treachery, describing the charter as 'a consummation of surrender=20
and treachery.'
  According to a press statement reporting on the agreement,=20
the pact between both parties was reached after secret and persistent=20
talks between the SIMM and the government during the last few=20
months. Machar reportedly surrendered to the government garrison=20
in Nasir on March 11, and was then flown to Khartoum.
  It is now reported that Machar had returned to Nasir in=20
southern Sudan to mobilize his forces, which will be transported=20
to Malakal and merged with the government forces to form a united=20
front that would undertake military operations against the SPLA=20
in the Bor area. SIMM, however, said in a statement issued on=20
May 26, that SPLA forces attacked its units at Pagak in Upper Nile=20
region, killing one man and wounding two.

=20
* SUDAN PLANE CRASHES =20

  A passenger plane, on a domestic flight, crashed near Khartoum,=20
killing all 47 passengers and six crew members. The plane, a=20
Russian-built Antonov 24 owned by the private Federal Airlines,=20
crashed at 10pm on May 3, when attempting to make an emergency landing.
  The flight originated in Waw in southern Sudan. It stopped in=20
El-Obied en route to Khartoum. When reaching Khartoum airport,=20
the visibility was <a name=L10003></a><a href=#L10004>so</a> poor due to a dust storm. The plane circled=20
at low altitude over Khartoum for 90 minutes before attempting an=20
emergency landing. The plane struck a newly-built, empty house in=20
the suburb of Haj Yousif, 9 miles north of Khartoum, killing all on board.
  This incident is the fifth in a series of plane disasters in the=20
last five months, which resulted in the killing of 144 people.=20
  In February, a military transport plane crashed near Jabal Awliya,=20
killing 91 people. In March, a cargo Antonov aircraft, which belonged=20
to the private Farnas company, crashed at El-Obied, but the 16=20
passengers and crew escaped unhurt. Two other planes crashed at=20
Waw airport.
  The incident provoked a row over the licensing of private=20
companies to operate passenger airlines, without proper regulations=20
to ensure sound technical and safety qualifications. The incident=20
was debated by the new parliament, after accusations were traded=20
between the Civil Aviation authority and Federal Airlines.=20
Aviation Minister, Tigani Adam al-Tahir, told members of=20
parliament that the plane captain had been warned that Khartoum=20
airport was closed. Federal Airlines said, in a statement, that=20
the plane had clearance to land at Khartoum airport and tried to=20
do <a name=L10004></a><a href=#L10005>so</a> eight times before it crashed in Haj Yousif. The Minister,=20
however, admitted shortcomings on the part of his ministry;=20
namely manpower and proper equipment.
  A pilot, interviewed by Sudan TV, was asked what he would do if=20
he encountered a technical problem while flying. He produced a small=20
book of the Koran from his pocket and said 'I will rely on this'.=20

=20
* SUDAN HUMAN RIGHTS =20

  The two leading human groups, Amnesty International (AI) and=20
Human Rights Watch (HRW), had both published reports on May 29,=20
accusing Sudan of continued human rights violations, including=20
slavery.
  AI report, titled 'Sudan: Progress or Public Relations?', details
the many atrocities committed by government forces, including the=20
deliberate and arbitrary killings of villagers, the abduction of
children, torture and ill-treatment of suspected government opponents.=20
  AI said children in Sudan were kidnapped and enslaved by troops and=20
militiamen. Some of the children are held for ransom, some appear to
be taken into domestic slavery while others end up in government
schools run like military camps. Some children have reportedly been=20
shot when trying to escape from these schools. AI urged UN members to=20
deploy human rights monitors in Sudan.
  The 259-page HRW report, 'Behind the Red Line: Political Repression=20
in Sudan', said violation of political and civil rights in Sudan is=20
the norm.
  HRW called for the UN to impose an arms embargo on all parties to=20
the civil war in Sudan in an effort to halt human rights abuses.
  Both groups accused the government of indiscriminately bombing=20
civilian areas in the south and carrying out a scorched-earth campaign=20
in a struggle the government has termed a "jihad," or holy war.=20
The report in March, by Caspar Biro, the UN human rights rapportuer=20
for Sudan, had made similar allegations.
  Both groups criticized rebel forces in the south for not protecting
human rights in the areas under their control, and accused them for
atrocities, including detention, looting, hostage-taking and summary
executions.


ECONOMIC POINTERS  =20

[] According to official sources, Sudan's total earnings from exports
   in the first quarter of this year was $120m, 55% less than=20
   anticipated by the budget. Inflation has also risen to 83.9%
   from 71% in December last year. Commodity prices has also risen by=20
   25% during February and March this year.

[] Sudan Lines had decided to sell off two of its fleet, to be able to
   partly pay its debt of $6m. The liners will be sold for $750,000 for
   'Nyala' and $2.2m for 'Marawi'.

  =20
[] Huge tariff increases were announced by the Nationality and=20
   Passport Department as follows:

                              Increased From          To
  New passport                    6,700 SP           15,000 SP
  Replacement passport            10,000             30,000
  Business passport               100,000            250,000
  Renewal of business passport    20,000             200,000
  Exit visa                       2,750              10,000

[] Following the closure of its kidney dialysis unit and its morgue,
   Khartoum Hospital, the largest in the country, had closed its=20
   operations' theater after six women died of poisoning under=20
   Cesarean surgery in mid-May. The hospital morgue was closed in March=20
   due to lack of funds to bury the bodies, and, therefore, had become=20
   full and could not receive any more bodies.

=20
* SHORT NEWS ITEMS   =20

-  Sudanese and Ugandan troops exchanged long range artillery fire=20
   across the borders as fierce battles raged on between the Uganda=20
   army and Oris rebels at Oraba trading center in northwestern=20
   Uganda on May 30. Sudanese troops were reported to have shelled=20
   Ugandan army positions at Keri and Kifwa Wazi from across the=20
   border. The Ugandan troops, in return, fired at Sudanese soldiers=20
   in Kaya.
   Uganda said the Sudanese army was giving cover for the rebels by=20
   targeting Ugandan military positions.=20
   The report claimed that the armed rebels wore Sudanese army uniforms.

-  A court in Sudan has, on May 30, sentenced six men to death by=20
   hanging and three to be crucified for armed robbery. Police said=20
   the robbers in Northern Darfur had 85 Kalashnikov rifles in their=20
   possession at the time of their arrest.
   Armed robbers in March attacked a convoy carrying Younis Sharif,=20
   the governor of Northern Darfur, wounding him and killing two of=20
   his bodyguards.

-  About 95 military men, jailed for an attempted coup in March, seized=20
   control of their prison in el-Duwaim and took the prisoner's=20
   commander, a major, hostage, a Sudanese daily reported on May 17.=20
   Al-Rai Al-Akhar (The Other View) newspaper said the soldiers and=20
   officers, on a hunger strike for several days, had rebelled and=20
   broke into the ammunition depot of the prison. The prisoners and=20
   security officers exchanged fire and four prison wardens were=20
   wounded in the clash.
   Following the publication of the news,  Al-Rai Al-Akhar was raided=20
   by an unidentified group of armed men who seized the newspaper's=20
   plates, a year's supply of newsprint, and 20,000 copies of the=20
   paper awaiting distribution.
   The government-run Press and Publication Council announced that=20
   the paper had been closed as a security measure and would only=20
   be allowed to resume publication if it denied the prison story.
   The Council said the report was harmful to army morale.
   The newspaper editor-in-chief, Mohi El-Din Titawi, said that his=20
   publication's account of the prison incident was true. He said he=20
   was expecting to be arrested any moment.
   Earlier last month, Akir Khabar (The Last News) was banned, leaving=20
   just two government-owned papers in the country.

-  Women who want to attend university in Sudan may be required to=20
   wear Islamic head coverings (hijab). The Sudanese daily Al-Ingaz=20
   Al-Watani quoted the Minister of Higher Education as saying he=20
   endorses the idea and believes it should start this year.=20
   Women students are also not allowed to use cosmetics while=20
   inside the university premises.

-  The President of the Sudanese Students General Union had revealed=20
   that 670 university students had been killed in the war in=20
   southern Sudan. He did not give any details.

-  Khartoum University authorities canceled student elections after=20
   clashes in which students set fire to and destroyed buildings=20
   and vehicles belonging to the faculty of arts. The university=20
   was a scene of violent confrontation between supporters and=20
   opponents of the government in early April. Riot police was sent=20
   in to break them up. =20
   Opposition students at al-Nilain University, on the other side of=20
   the city, tried to march into central Khartoum in solidarity with=20
   their colleagues at Khartoum University but police fired teargas=20
   to disperse them. Several students were hurt.

-  Yemen has decided to terminate the contracts of 1,500 Sudanese=20
   teachers and send them home.
   The Yemeni government had informed the Sudanese Embassy in Sana'a=20
   <a name=L10005></a><a href=#L10006>so</a> it could take steps to prepare for the teachers' return.


