From: erma@web.apc.org
Newsgroups: africa.horn
Subject: Eritrean Dinner - June 21 Toronto
Date: 10 Jun 1996 15:39:20 -0500 (EST)

Eritrean Dinner with Nura
 
Enjoy a relaxing evening of Eritrean food with guest speaker Nura Mohamed,
NGO worker with Eritrean Relief Association, ex-fighter, mother and currently
Eritrea's Consul to Canada
 
Place:  Afro Sports Club
        1940 Eglinton Ave. W., Toronto
        (West of Dufferin)
 
Date:   Friday 21 June 1996
 
Time:   Gathering  7:00pm
        Dinner     7:30pm
 
Cost:   $20 per person (Cash bar)
 
RSVP by June 18 
by phone:  (416) 532 7320 or 
e-mail:    erma@web.apc.org
 
Please indicate preference for vegetarian or non vegetarian food
 
Co sponsored by ERITREE and Earthroots Working together to rebuild Eritrea's
ecosystem through The Baobab Project
 
6 June 1996
 
We were delighted when Nura Mohamed, Eritrea's Consul to Canada agreed to
speak at ERITREE's dinner on June 21st 1996. 
     Nura has a strong background in the NGO field as a staff person for the
Eritrean Relief Association in both Khartoum and Asmara. 
     For Canadians this is an exceptional opportunity to hear from a woman
who was a fighter in Eritrea's 30 year war, is well versed in international
development work and is now living with her daughter in Ottawa.
     Women in Eritrea have over those 30+ years come from being no more than
possessions of men to have a place on councils at all levels of government,
the right to own land, the right to education and to make decisions which
determine their own future. Women were active combatants during the war,
making up about one third of the active fighters by the end of the war in
1991. Men also changed, taking on responsibilities previously unheard of, 
such
as childcare and cooking.
     Now that the war has been over for five years women are still struggling
to hold on to their independence as Eritrean society adjusts to the different
expectations of returning expatriots, Eritreans who were under the Ethiopian
Dergue for the duration of the war, and those who fought and practiced new
ways of living in liberated areas during the war.
 
Prepare yourself for a stimulating evening of discussion, Eritrean food, 
music
and gentle company.
Hope to see you on the 21st,
 
Gebremichael Isaac
Chair, ERITREE
 
 

 
x
.
